<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea's Won Continues Depreciation While Shares Tumbling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar soared to 2,000
against the South Korean won Tuesday from the previous day's 1,850
at the Seoul foreign exchange market, the first time in history.
</P>
<P>
In the meanwhile, the composite stock price index plunged 29.7
points, or 7.5 percent to 366.36 points, an unprecedented loss in
history, with a turnover standing at 85.89 million shares worth 1
trillion won (615.93 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Market officials attributed the won's sharp depreciation to
"unnecessary uneasiness" caused by reports of an acute shortage of
foreign exchange in near future.
</P>
<P>
The worsening situation came a day after some international
financial organizations further downgraded the country's credit in the
world's financial market.
</P>
<P>
The downgrading credit is expected to worsen the foreign-currency
situation and the Korean conglomerates and financial institutions will
find it nearly impossible to secure hard currency from abroad,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
South Korea has been in serious financial crisis caused by the
collapse of a group of conglomerates and bad loans of financial
institutions. It has signed an agreement with the International
Monetary Fund for a bailout loan valued at 57 billion U.S. dollars
with tough conditions.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, South Korea will restructure its economy, open
its financial market and cut its budget while it has to face massive
layoffs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
