<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Factory Orders for Durable Goods Rise 4.8 Pct </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Orders to U.S. factories
for durable goods went up 4.8 percent in November, the largest
increase in five years, the Commerce Department reported here
today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that orders for durable goods, products
expected to last more than three years, totaled a record,
seasonally adjusted 195 billion U.S. dollars, up from 186.1
billion dollars in October.
</P>
<P>
It was the biggest advance since a 7.5 percent growth in
December 1992.
</P>
<P>
Transportation orders shot up 20.3 percent, the biggest gain
since a 38.2 percent jump in July 1991. If excluding
transportation, orders slipped 0.2 percent, the second straight
decline.
</P>
<P>
Orders for primary metals climbed up 3.2 percent and for
electronic and other electrical equipment, up 0.1 percent. But
orders for industrial machinery and equipment fell 1.6 percent,
the third drop in four months.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, orders for military goods shot up by 24.9 percent
after falling 13.5 percent a month earlier. Orders for nonmilitary
capital goods excluding aircraft fell 2 percent, the second
straight decrease
</P>
<P>
The backlog of unfilled orders increased 2.4 percent, the sixth
increase in the last seven months. A growing backlog often
suggests businesses are unable to meet demand with current
facilities and manpower.
</P>
<P>
But shipments, a measure of current demand, fell l0.4 percent,
the third drop in four months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
