<DOCNO> XIE19971224.0005 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eating Chicken Is Safe: HK Health Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Eating chicken is safe so
long as they are well-cooked, a Hong Kong health official said
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
But anyone who has been in contact with chicken should wash the
hands thoroughly, said Paul Saw, Deputy Director of Health and
Chairman of the Inter-Department Coordinating Committee on
Influenza A H5N1.
</P>
<P>
The export of chicken from China's inland to Hong Kong would be
temporarily suspended from Tuesday midnight to allow for
appropriate controls to be instructed, said Saw.
</P>
<P>
This voluntary measure by the inland authorities was revealed
at a press conference after the committee's meeting Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Evidence so far suggested exposure to chicken or its feces as a
possible source of infection of the avian virus, while direct
man-to-man transmission needed to be determined, he said.
</P>
<P>
The virus could be easily killed through cleansing using common
disinfectants, he added.
</P>
<P>
The temporary suspension was introduced as a precautionary
measure and to ensure the health status of chickens imported into
Hong Kong in the future, said Leslie Sims, senior veterinary
officer of the Agriculture and Fisheries Department (AFD), at the
press conference.
</P>
<P>
When chickens are imported again from the inland, the AFD would
have to be in place for screening for evidence of Flu A infection
using a rapid blood test for imported birds.
</P>
<P>
"The laboratory would be working shifts to ensure that initial
testing is completed before the birds are sold the following
morning," Sims said.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime. the AFD would continue testing all local
chicken farms for the H5N1 virus, with such testing to be
completed within 10 days.
</P>
<P>
Results available so far found H5N1 virus in two swabs of
chicken droppings collected 10 days ago from two market stalls and
the whole batch of chickens had been handed over to AFD for
destruction and the market stalls were thoroughly cleansed
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The AFD would continue to monitor the situation and take
appropriate action where necessary," he said.
</P>
<P>
The preventive measures which had been proposed by the
Inter-Department Coordinating Committee had been implemented
smoothly, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Health has stepped up surveillance for Flu A
H5N1 at public clinics and hospitals since early this month and
private doctors had been solicited, for any more cases of
infection of the virus to be picked up, Saw said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
