<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Faction Leaders Foresee Peace in Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Somalia's faction leaders today
voiced the conviction that peace and stability will prevail in
their country.
</P>
<P>
The Somali Declaration of Principles signed here Monday will
work to end the conflicts, and bring peace and reconciliation to
Somalia, said Hussein Mohamed Aideed and Ali Mahdi Mohammed after
meeting with Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa.
</P>
<P>
Aideed, leader of the Somali National Alliance, said they
discussed with Moussa the declaration and issues related to its
implementation.
</P>
<P>
He said the declaration would furnish the "cornerstone for
realizing Somalia's national unity."
</P>
<P>
Ali Mahdi, leader of the 26-faction National Salvation Council,
chimed in with Aideed to seek the support of the Arab League and
the international community to restore stability to the nation of
the Horn of Africa.
</P>
<P>
Aideed and Mahdi, leaders of Somalia's strongest factions,
signed the declaration, the country's first comprehensive
power-sharing agreement, which calls for independence, integrity
and security of Somalia.
</P>
<P>
Under the declaration, Somalia will hold a National
Reconciliation Conference to elect a 13-member Presidential
Council, set up a national government, Council of Deputies and
independent judicial body.
</P>
<P>
If the declaration works, it will help form the first unified
national government in Somalia since the 1991 ouster of the late
dictator Mohamed Siad Barre.
</P>
<P>
Since then Somalia has been fragmented into fiefdoms protected
by faction leaders, who have never fully carried out the peace
deals reached between them. The factional armed conflicts,
combined with a 1992 famine, have claimed about 300,000 lives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
