<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US GDP Grows at 3.1 Pct Annual Rate in Third Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. economy grew at a
robust 3.1 percent annual rate during the third quarter, the
Commerce Department reported here today.
</P>
<P>
The department said the growth in the gross domestic product
(GDP), the total output of goods and services in this country, was
little dip from the April-June 3.3 percent rate.
</P>
<P>
Despite its continued growth, the economy so far has not
increased price pressures. In fact, a measure tied to the GDP rose
just 1.4 percent at an annual rate, the smallest increase in five
years.
</P>
<P>
Contrary to some economists' earlier predictions, the U.S.
economy continued the speed at nearly the same rate of the
April-June quarter, although that was down from an even stronger
4.9 percent in the January-March period, the department said in
its final revision of third-quarter data.
</P>
<P>
However, many analysts expect the financial chaos in east Asia
to curb economic growth during 1998 and also help the U.S. Federal
Reserve maintain the short-term interest rates steady to prevent
inflation. They are forecasting a growth rate of between 2 percent
and 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The department said the revision to the third-quarter GDP, from
an estimated 3.3 percent a month ago, reflected small downward
changes in most major components.
</P>
<P>
Consumer spending increased at a 5.6 percent annual rate, a
small drop from the 5.8 percent earlier estimate. It had slipped
to a 0.9 percent gain in the second quarter after jumping 5.3
percent in the first.
</P>
<P>
Consumer spending, which represents two-thirds of the nation's
economic activity, is believed to have slowed in the
October-December quarter, although some experts believe it
remained strong due to solid job and income growth.
</P>
<P>
Business spending on equipment such as computers and
communications gear was unchanged at a 24.1 percent annual growth,
a little pickup from 23 percent in the second quarter and the best
since the final three months of 1983.
</P>
<P>
Residential construction rose at a 2.7 percent rate, down from
the 3.7 percent estimate last month and 7.4 percent from the
second quarter.
</P>
<P>
Increases in business inventories slowed to 47.5 billion U.S.
dollars in the third quarter from 77.6 billion dollars in the
second. And exports of goods and services grew at just a 4.4
percent rate as against 18.4 percent from April through June.
</P>
<P>
The various changes put the economy's output in the third
quarter at a seasonally and inflation-adjusted annual rate of 7.21
trillion dollars, according to the department report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971224.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-Up: Moi Tips to Win Re-Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 23 (Xinhua) -- With six days to go for the
December 29 General Election, Kenyan people, media and foreign
observers predict that the incumbent President Daniel arap Moi
will be re-elected as president for his last term in office.
</P>
<P>
Moi will lead the ruling Kenya African National Union (KANU)
to win another parliamentary majority in the Eighth Parliament,
they estimate.
</P>
<P>
The question in the minds of Moi's campaigners is not whether
they will win the presidential, parliamentary and civic elections
on the polling day but how big the win will be.
</P>
<P>
An article of the weekly East African entitled "Moi and KANU
Look Set for a New Victory" said that in terms of organization
alone, Moi "enjoys the advantage of incumbency and the logistical
apparatus of state that this puts at his disposal, not to mention
a nationwide party structure built unchallenged over the last
three decades."
</P>
<P>
The article noted that the ruling party had sufficient
campaign funds and quoted reliable estimates as putting it in the
region of 158 million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
"No other political party, or even all of them combined, could
command this amount of support," added the article which was
carried last month by the weekly.
</P>
<P>
Though opposition parties criticize Moi for mismanagement,
corruption and deteriorating living standards in the past five
years, Moi can take an advantage of the divisions among the
Opposition.
</P>
<P>
There have been periodic attempts to forge some sort of
anti-KANU stance but they have been more rhetorical than
substantive, the article stressed.
</P>
<P>
This time round, the Opposition is even more splintered than
in the first multi-party election in 1992, the article said,
adding that this year the Opposition fielded 14 presidential
candidates, compared with seven in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Most foreign observers and many local independent analysts
also predict that Moi and his ruling KANU are favorites to win
the presidency and a parliamentary majority.
</P>
<P>
However, Moi, in power since 1978, has a fight to win on the
first ballot and avoid an unprecedented second round run-off
against an opposition upstart.
</P>
<P>
The opposition parties recognizes that a single opposition
presidential candidate offers them the best chance in the
presidential race. But they have no mechanisms to choose such a
candidate.
</P>
<P>
So, the Opposition has settled on their second best strategy
to lock President Moi out of at least four provinces of Kenya's
eight provinces, thereby forcing a run-off.
</P>
<P>
Under Kenya's Constitution, the president-elect must collect
at least 25 percent of the vote in at least five of Kenya's eight
provinces.
</P>
<P>
Moi, 73, who is seeking a final five-year term for presidency,
managed to get more than 25 percent of the votes cast during the
last General Election in Rift Valley, Western, Coast, Eastern and
Northeastern provinces.
</P>
<P>
According to the Opposition's strategy this time round,
presidential candidate Michael Wamalwa of opposition Ford-Kenya
will lock Moi out in Western Province while presidential
candidates Mwai Kibaki and Charity Ngilu will lock him out in
Central and Eastern provinces respectively. And so on to the
run-off.
</P>
<P>
Considering that Moi had 39 percent of the vote in Western
province in 1992, local analysts said, it looks unlikely for
Wamalwa to whip up a more than 14 percent anti-Moi swing.
</P>
<P>
They noted that the decisive battle-front is likely to be East
province where Ngilu, Presidential candidate for the opposition
Social Democratic Party, has strong backing from her Kamba
people.
</P>
<P>
Ngilu, Kenya's first female candidate for the presidency,
could stop President Moi from getting the 25 percent of the vote
in Eastern Province which Moi secured in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Another article under the title of "The Opposition Blew a
Golden Chance" pointed out that to win this election, Opposition
leaders would need to be more clear-minded than they have been.
</P>
<P>
To win this election, it said, they need to make sacrifices
but they probably are not ready to, adding that many of them
would have to forgo their personal ambitions for the time being.
</P>
<P>
Wachira Maina, author of the article and constitutional
lawyer, put it right when he said, "since they are not ready to
do any of these things, I have no doubt they have already lost
the election." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
