<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Launches Socio-Economic Surveys in Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Economic Commission for Africa (ECA) today officially launched
the comprehensive socio-economic surveys in rural areas of
Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here, chief of ECA's food
security and sustainable development division P.
Makinwa-Adebusoye said the socio-economic surveys were conducted
in seven regions in Ethiopia, namely Afar, Amhara,
Benshangul-Gumuz, Gambells, Shouther Region, Tigray and Somalia
with over 1,000 questions.
</P>
<P>
According to the division chief, the survey results have been
produced in very comprehensive documents numbering 12 volumes.
</P>
<P>
These documents contain 4,000 statistical tables supported by
500 pages of detailed analysis. A total of 25,000 farmers
responded to the questions that were asked and 1,500 extension
agents and rural development assistants participated in the
surveys.
</P>
<P>
"This is the first time that socio-economic surveys of such
magnitude have been conducted in Ethiopia at household levels.
This is also the first time that a comprehensive data system has
been generated for such regions as Gambella, Benshangui-Gumuz,
Somali, Afar and southern regions," she said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to major findings of the socio-economic surveys in
Ethiopia, the ECA division chief said, the average family size of
the rural surveyed households ranges from six to seven.
</P>
<P>
On illiteracy status in the surveyed regions, the division
chief said that a large proportion of the population in the
sample areas were reported to be illiterate, i.e. in Afar 77.8
percent, Amhara 69.5 percent, Tigray 69.1 percent,
Benshangul-Gumuz 64.8 percent, Gambella 64.2 percent and southern
region 59.0 percent.
</P>
<P>
"The survey result also revealed the fact that in all the
survey areas, female illiteracy rates were higher than that of
males," she added.
</P>
<P>
According to the ECA division chief, in all the surveyed
areas, except in Afar, over 90 percent of the farmers have their
own farmland.
</P>
<P>
However, the survey results revealed that the major problem
for the population in the rural areas are small size of farmland
and fragmentation.
</P>
<P>
The problem of small farm sizes in the arid and semi-arid
areas of Ethiopia is a major problem for any agricultural
transformation process.
</P>
<P>
Most of the farmers in the surveyed regions believe that they
do not possess enough farmland to sustain the given families.
</P>
<P>
She said, the survey results indicate that an overwhelming
majority of the housing units have one or two rooms, adding that
given the average family size which is between six and seven, it
is very clear that most of the dwelling units are overcrowded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
