<HEADLINE> Zambia's Inter-Party Dialogue "not Window </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The proposed inter-party
dialogue is not propaganda strategy designed as window dressing
to impress donors but rather is for the enhancement of democracy
in the country, a senior official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Co-chairman of the inter-party dialogue, ruling party national
secretary, Micheal Sata made the remarks at a news briefing after
meeting with co-chairman Mainza Chona of the United National
Independence Party led by former President Kenneth Kaunda and
secretary of the talks Guy Scott of the Lima Party.
</P>
<P>
He condemned Liberal Progressive Front President Roger
Chongwe's statement that President Frederick Chiluba has made a
secret pact with some opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
Sata, who doubles as Minister without Portfolio, said that
Chongwe, who has been away from the country since the October 28
coup attempt, is not interested in helping to settle the destiny
of Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Sata also accused UNIP leader Kaunda of insulting Chiluba by
calling him unpredictable, adding that he took strong exception
to anyone insulting his president.
</P>
<P>
Co-chairman Chona refuted Sata's accusation, saying that
calling a party unpredictable is not an insult and cautioned Sata
not to stray from the issue at hand which is the preparatory
meeting to the dialogue.
</P>
<P>
Chona said the three are happy with the progress toward the
talks to be attended by party presidents next month to discuss
the contentious issues facing the country.
</P>
<P>
At the preliminary meeting held early this month, 31 parties
drew an agenda for the inter-party dialogue.
</P>
<P>
The party presidents will follow the agenda, which includes
most contentious issues like constitution, electoral process and
voters' register and fresh registration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
