<HEADLINE> Mozambican City Alert Over Cholera </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Maputo, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique's second largest
city Beira has been put on alert over the danger of a cholera
outbreak, which has taken a toll of 253 since August in other
parts of the southern African country.
</P>
<P>
A media report said today that the port city in central
Mozambique has since Saturday launched a massive clean-up
campaign.
</P>
<P>
About 800 people were mobilized on the first day, the report
said, adding that several hundreds others have volunteered to
work as cleaners in exchange for food.
</P>
<P>
While removing rubbishes in streets, the government has also
closed all the food boothes at the Tchungamoio market, as they
are the most likely channel of disease spreading.
</P>
<P>
The report said authorities are to recruit about 400 people
who will engage in a house-to-house health education program.
Water additives capable of killing cholera virus are also to be
distributed to citizens.
</P>
<P>
Cholera broke out in Mozambique's capital Maputo and Maputo
Province in the south in August and has since spread to
neighboring Gaza, Inhambane and Manica provinces. A total of
8,228 patients have been reported so far.
</P>
<P>
Averttino Barreto, a senior national health official who
recently visited Beira said many places in the city are in the
danger of cholera invasion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
