<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-23 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Reiterates Support to Land-for-Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA (PALESTINE), December 23 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chinese
Vice-Premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen reiterated here
today that the Chinese government supports land-for-peace
principle in the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Qian made the statement when he met with Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat in his office in Gaza
city.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese minister said, "China supports the Middle East
peace process and it is very much concerned about the
impasse of the peace march."
</P>
<P>
He said, "the main reason for the stalemate is that the current
Israeli government has not honored its previous government's
commitment to the land-for-peace principle agreed by all sides
concerned at the Madrid peace conference." Therefore, he urged
the Israeli government to abide by U.N. resolutions and the
land-for-peace principle so as to push the peace process forward.
</P>
<P>
He said, "China appreciates the stance taken by the PNA in
resolving the Palestinian-Israeli dispute through peaceful
negotiations. And China will continue to support the PNA to
promote peace in a flexible and pragmatic way."
</P>
<P>
Arafat briefed Qian Qichen on the latest developments in the
Middle East and expressed hope that China would play a greater
role in getting the peace process moving.
</P>
<P>
He said that the impasse of the process would create more
problems for the whole region, citing economic difficultities of
the Palestinian self-rule area as a result of the blockade by
Israeli authorities.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Arafat expressed his thanks to the
Chinese government and people who, according to him, have
rendered cordial aid and support to the Palestinians in time
of needs.
</P>
<P>
Qian also briefed Arafat on his visits to Lebanon and
Syria and also his talks with Israeli leaders prior to his
visit to Gaza. He said, "China supports the just cause of
the Palestinians and believes that they should have their own
state."
</P>
<P>
Qian also met and had talks with PNA Minister of Planning
and International Cooperation Nabil Shaath. The two sides signed
three documents of cooperation under which China will provide a
loan and help the PNA to build a road in the self-rule
area.
</P>
<P>
Gaza is the fourth leg of Qian's Middle East tour which
has taken him to Lebanon, Syria and Israel. He will also
visit Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
