<HEADLINE> Turkey Blasts Greek Expulsion of Turkish Diplomat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Turkey accused Greece of
expelling a Turkish diplomat in retaliation for the expulsion of
a Greek diplomat by Turkey Monday, said a Turkish official
statement released today.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry statement said that Greece today asked
Administrative Attache Nedin Ozergin in Turkey's General
Consulate in Thessaloniki, northern city of Greece, to leave the
country.
</P>
<P>
Turkey Monday ordered Greek Administrative Official Efstratios
Haralambous to leave the country within one week due to his
alleged involvement in espionage.
</P>
<P>
The statement added that Greece's act of retaliation against
Turkey's expulsion of the Greek diplomat was "baseless."
</P>
<P>
Turkey accused Haralambous, who served in Greek General
Consulate in Turkey's largest city of Istanbul, of spying for
Turkey's outlawed Kurdish Worker's Party (PKK).
</P>
<P>
Turkey has been criticizing Greece for allegedly providing
political, financial and military support to the PKK.
</P>
<P>
The Greek government has rejected the Turkish claims, saying
that Ankara has failed to substantiate them.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a 13-year-old separatist war against
the Turkish government in eastern and southeastern Turkey for an
independent Kurdish state in the area.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Greece, both members of the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization, have long been at odds over several issues
including the limits of air space and the Aegean Sea, rights
to sea-bed minerals and the Cyprus problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
