<HEADLINE> UK's State-Owned BNFL, Magnox Agree to Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Britain's state-owned nuclear
operations -- British Nuclear Fuels Limited and Magnox Electric --
will merge next year.
</P>
<P>
The merger will be supported by a 3.7 billion pound (5.92
billion US dollar) undertaking from the government to cover
clear-up costs, according to an official announcement released
here today.
</P>
<P>
Energy Minister John Battle said the government expected the
merged group "to reduce substantially" the costs of eventually
closing Magnox nuclear reactors and leaning the sites.
</P>
<P>
Integration of BNFL, the fuel reprocessing business, and
Magnox, the nuclear generator, has been planned since Magnox was
separated from the newer nuclear fleet privatized with British
Energy last year.
</P>
<P>
The merger includes a clawback incentive program, which means
both the nuclear business and the government can benefit equally
from cost reductions on the liabilities of up to 1.6 billion
pounds (2.56 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
However, the merger could result in the loss of about 10
percent of the combined companies' workforce of more than 19,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
