<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coca-Cola to Acquire French Beverage Company </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The deal, which has Coca-Cola purchasing all Orangina brands
and four bottling and concentrate plants, is to give the U.S.
company a 58 percent share of the French soda market, according
to newspaper reports here today.
</P>
<P>
Coca-Cola already has a dominant position in France,
commanding a 49.6 percent market share, the Wall Street Journal
reported. Meanwhile, Orangina, a carbonated drink that contains
orange juice and pulp and has been a fierce rival to Coke, is
France's most popular noncola soft drink, with a market share of
about 8.5 percent. Combined, the two would dwarf rivals, such as
Pepsi, which in 1996 had a market share of 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
This competition now extends to a noncola product, according
to analysts. The planned acquisition surprised many industry
executives because of Pernod Ricard's bitter relationship in
recent years with Coca-Cola, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
In January this year, France's antitrust authority fined Coke
1.8 million U.S. dollars for anticompetitive practices in the
early 1990s, following a complaint from Orangina. In addition,
Pernod Ricard distributes Pepsi products in restaurants and bars
in France. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971224.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Scale for Apportioning UN Membership Dues Adopted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The General Assembly of
the United Nations has adopted a new scale of assessments for
1998-2000 that remains a ceiling rate of 25 percent but lowers the
floor rate to 0.001 percent, a release from the spokesman's office
said today.
</P>
<P>
Adopting the resolution without a vote late Monday night, which
sets out exactly what percent each country will pay, the assembly
also decided to consider reviewing the scale for the period of
1999-2000 in the coming months, in the light of "all relevant
factors, including the periodic reports of the secretary-general
on the status of contributions."
</P>
<P>
The release said the 185-member assembly firmly rejected any
change in the United States payments.
</P>
<P>
In responding to the provision, the European Union said it
would agree to open the scale discussions only after the United
States had adopted legally binding provisions to clear its arrears
in full and respect its financial obligations under the Charter of
the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Any unilateral reduction of the amounts owed to the
organization by the United States could not be accepted, the
European Union added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
