<HEADLINE> Plane Crashes in Libya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS, December 23 (Xinhua) -- A Libyan BA 310 plane crashed
today in northern Libya as it made a forced landing along a
highway, resulting in serious burns and injuries of its five crew
members.
</P>
<P>
According to a Libyan news agency report received here, the
plane was on its way from northern coastal city of Sert to
Tripoli, but had to make forced landing on a highway some 25
kilometers south of the city of Beni Walid. The plane crashed and
went ablaze.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Tripoli airport sources as saying that the
plane encountered technical trouble, attributing this to the
serious shortage of spare parts facing the aviation sector as a
result of the embargo imposed against Libya.
</P>
<P>
Libya is facing an international embargo since 1992 for having
failed to hand over two Libyan citizens suspected of involvement
in the bombing of a U.S. passenger plane over Lockerbie, Scotland,
in 1988, causing the death of 270 people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
