<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Urgently Needs 26,000 Tons of Relief Food </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Zambian Vice-president
Christon Tembo said here today that his country urgently needs
26,000 tons of relief maize to feed people in 29 districts at an
estimated cost of eight million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Addressing donors over the food security situation in the
country at Lulungushi International Conference Center in Lusaka,
Tembo said that about one million people in 29 districts have
lost their crops, seeds, animals due to floods and droughts and
need urgent food relief.
</P>
<P>
He added that about 8.5 million Dollars, inclusive of internal
transportation, handling and storage, will be needed to allocate
the relief food locally to cover the period from December this
year to March 1998.
</P>
<P>
Tembo stated that his office is carrying further assessment of
seven more districts where starvation is looming, adding that the
number of affected districts could rise to 36.
</P>
<P>
There is enough food in the country, but the government has no
money to spend on the relief program, said Tembo. He appealed to
the donor community to render financial support.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that Zambia, with a population of over
nine million, needs to import 270,000 tons of maize to guarantee
the country's food security in the 1997-1998 agricultural season
in preparations against the upcoming El Nino. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
