<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cairo Agreement Threatening Peace in Somalia: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 23 (Xinhua) -- A senior Ethiopia
diplomat today said the agreement reached among Somali rival
faction leaders in Cairo "is a threat to peace in Somalia".
</P>
<P>
According to the Ethiopian News Agency, the diplomat said "the
agreement which does not include all members of the National
Salvation Council (NSC) marks the 'beginning of a dangerous
situation' in the war-torn Somalia."
</P>
<P>
He noted that the Somali problem could be resolved sustainably
provided that an agreement is reached through negotiations in
which all clans are represented, adding that a reconciliation
that excludes particular clans would only foment further
divisions and instability.
</P>
<P>
"The Cairo agreement which excludes a big clan in northern
Somalia could also provoke uneasiness among the Hawiyee and the
non-Hawiyee clans in southern Somalia," the diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
He said, the Cairo agreement has not won the approval of all
members of the NSC.
</P>
<P>
The diplomat said, the attempt by Egypt to win publicity by
hijacking the Somali reconciliation process would only worsen the
situation in the war-ravaged state.
</P>
<P>
He said the Cairo agreement has breached the Sodere agreement
which has flickered a glimmer of hope to lasting peace in
Somalia.
</P>
<P>
The diplomat also said Ethiopia which is directly affected by
the problems in Somalia would endeavor to ensure sustainable
peace there.
</P>
<P>
The existing socio-economic and political relations between
Ethiopia and Somalia makes Ethiopia's role in the latter
irreplaceable by any other party, the diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
Two co-chairmen of the NSC of Somalia, Aden Abdullahi Nur and
Abdullahi Yusuf Ahmed, yesterday issued a press statement here,
condemning the Egyptian Foreign Ministry spokesman's statement on
Somali reconciliation talks in Cairo and dismissing the statement
as irresponsible and misleading to the international community.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
