<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Troops Shell South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Israeli troops bombarded
Lebanese southern provinces throughout Tuesday in retaliation for
a Muslim guerrillas' attack which left three Israeli soldiers
wounded earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese official National News Agency said Israeli troops
shelled a Lebanese army barrack and nearby villages in Nabatiye, a
southern province facing the Israeli-occupied border enclave this
morning, but didn't cause any casualties.
</P>
<P>
Israeli troops then extended their shelling, which was
accompanied by heavy gun fires, to another villages in the same
province where the three Israeli soldiers were blown up.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Israeli warplanes hovered low over Nabatiye
and Iqlim Toufaha, another province near the occupation zone,
making mock air raids, the agency added.
</P>
<P>
Early this morning, a guerrilla unit donated a roadside bomb
when an Israeli patrol was traveling on the way from the village
of Rihan to Sujoud, both in the Israeli self-styled security zone,
a guerrilla's statement said.
</P>
<P>
An Israeli officer and two soldiers were wounded in the
explosion and their call for help could be heard nearby, the
statement added.
</P>
<P>
Israeli radio confirmed the explosion and admitted three
soldiers were injured by the attack.
</P>
<P>
The conflicts between Israeli troops and Lebanese guerrillas
have lasted since Israel carved out an estimated
1,200-square-kilometer area in south Lebanon in 1985 to prevent
cross-border attacks in its northern areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
