<HEADLINE> Primakov: China, Priority in Russian Foreign Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Russia's foreign policy in the
outgoing year was oriented to the development of relations with
leading Asian countries, especially with China, Russian Foreign
Minister Yevgeny Primakov said today.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference, the minister said that Russia's foreign
policy had a considerable advance in relations with China, a
strong pole in the shaping multi-polar world.
</P>
<P>
Primakov noted the 4,200 kilometer stretch of the
Russian-Chinese border was demarcated in the course of the year
and the two sides for the first time reached agreement on detente
in the border zone and the pullback of armed forces by both sides.
</P>
<P>
"The development of Russia's relations with China is aimed at
strategic cooperation in the 21st century, and the solution of
border problems created a model for the solution of similar
problems in the Asia-Pacific region."
</P>
<P>
Primakov also noted a breakthrough in Russian-Japanese
relations in 1997, saying the two countries had a sober approach
to the problem of bilateral relations and aimed at vigorous and
successful development of their economic ties.
</P>
<P>
On relations with countries of the Commonwealth of Independent
States, the minister called for stepping up the CIS integration,
including at an inter-sectoral level.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of Russia-Belorussia relations, Primakov stressed that
the Russian Foreign Ministry set a great value on the
Russia-Belorussia Union in which "the states that have common
historical roots are uniting and cooperating in a larger extent
than previously."
</P>
<P>
He also mentioned the successes in normalization of Russia's
relations with Ukraine, saying it had abolished a whole number of
contradictions in their relations and opened a way to their further
development.
</P>
<P>
As for relations with the Baltic states, Primakov said there
had been a sequence of "positive shifts" on this track. A very
serious talk had started which would help abolish obstacles in the
development of Russia's relations with the Baltic states, he
noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
