<HEADLINE> Mbeki's Aide May Face Homicide Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 23 (Xinhua) -- South African Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki's media spokesman, Thami Ntenteni, may face
charges of culpable homicide following a collision near
Johannesburg on Monday night, South African Press Association
reported today.
</P>
<P>
A woman involved in the accident died this afternoon and three
other victims, one woman and two men, were in a critical
condition, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Ntenteni was arrested for drunken and negligent driving but
then released with a written warning to appear in the Wynberg
Magistrate's Court on January 5.
</P>
<P>
The accident occurred in Midrand, a town between Johannesburg
and Pretoria, at about 9 p.m. on Monday, in which four people
were seriously injured when the car they were traveling in caught
fire after being hit from behind by another car.
</P>
<P>
Their car left the road and overturned. By the time emergency
personnel arrived at the scene, the victims were still trapped in
the car, a large part of which had burnt out, police said.
</P>
<P>
"This matter is being dealt with by the South African Police
Service and is subject to their normal investigative procedure,"
Mbeki's spokesman Ricky Naidoo said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Road accidents usually peak at the Christmas season in South
Africa when traffic on national routes are heavy with holiday
makers.
</P>
<P>
So far, 468 people have lost their lives on South African
roads since the beginning of the month, the traffic authorities
said. Most of the accidents were caused by speeding.
</P>
<P>
Last year, a total of 1,242 people died during the festive
season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
