<HEADLINE> US Firms Allowed to Bid for Turkey Chopper Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The United States today
authorized U.S. firms to compete for a contract to supply attack
helicopters to Turkey, a State Department spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Following a joint State Department and Pentagon review of
requests by American companies, Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright "today decided to allow U.S. participation in this
competition," State Department spokesman James Foley said.
</P>
<P>
"Her decision is fully consistent with our policy concerning
arms transfers to Turkey," Foley said. "We seek to support this
important NATO ally's efforts to meet its legitimate self-defense
requirements, and to fulfill its NATO commitments."
</P>
<P>
The State Department had approved marketing licenses allowing
U.S. companies to export technical information about their attack
helicopters so that they could formulate competitive bids.
</P>
<P>
He said this did not automatically entail a license to export
such helicopters to Turkey, for which a separate decision would be
needed should a U.S. firm win the Turkish competition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
