<HEADLINE> World Bodies Join Hands with Nigeria in Drug War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Some world organizations have
jointly decided that the existing facilities within the Nigerian
Drug Law Enforcement Agency (NDLEA) will be reinforced through
logistic and technical assistance.
</P>
<P>
These world bodies are the United Nations Drug Control Program
(UNDCP), Interpol and World Customs Organization, the Nigerian
Television Authority reported tonight.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, this was announced by the leader of
an international visitation team to Nigeria on drug control, who
is UNDCP's regional officer for west and central Africa, when the
four-man team visited NDLEA Chairman Musa Bamaiyi as part of
their seven-nation mission tour.
</P>
<P>
He said the decision was taken at the recognition of the fact
that there was definite proof of success on the part of Nigeria
in its fight to contain the abuse of drug pills and trafficking.
</P>
<P>
The team chose to visit Nigeria because they were impressed
with NDLEA's integrated approach system of simultaneously
fighting supply and demand reduction, he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is certainly the way of the future," he pointed out,
adding that NDLEA was a very viable partner that could not be
ignored in the global effort to combat the drug problem.
</P>
<P>
In his response, Bamaiyi reassured the visitors that Nigeria
as a sovereign entity would continue to address the drug
phenomenon not in an effort to please any other country but to
salvage its society from the devastating scourge.
</P>
<P>
He said the level of achievement so far recorded could be
traced to dedication of the remaining staff of the agency after
flushing out about 1,000 others in its determination to have a
corrupt-free law enforcement agency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
