<HEADLINE> South Africa Registers Trade Deficit in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 23 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's monthly
trade account swung into deficit in November after surprising the
market in October with an impressive surplus of 1.73 billion Rand
(360 million U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Customs figures released today showed that imports exceeded
exports by 73.7 million Rand (15.3 million Dollars) last month, a
disappointing deficit following a strong pick-up in exports over
the year, the South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
The cumulative trade surplus declined to 11.37 billion Rand
(2.37 billion Dollars) from 11.45 billion (2.38 billion Dollars)
at the end of October.
</P>
<P>
Exports dropped sharply to 10.9 billion Rand (2.27 billion
Dollars) from 14.7 billion Rand (3.06 billion Dollars) in
October, while imports declined from 11.21 billion Rand (2.34
billion Dollars) to 11 billion (2.29 billion Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Cumulative exports at 130.7 billion Rand (27.2 billion
Dollars) were 13.1 percent up on the same period last year, with
imports of 119.3 billion Rand (24.9 billion Dollars), some 11.5
percent higher. 
</P>
</TEXT>
