<DOCNO> XIE19971224.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Announces Support for Women, Children Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission, the
European Union (EU)'s executive body, today expressed its support
for projects to combat violence against women and children.
</P>
<P>
Anita Gradin, European commissioner responsible for justice and
home affairs, Tuesday announced the Commission's support for 47
such projects under the DAPHNE initiative.
</P>
<P>
Gradin said that the initiative "clearly meets a deeply felt
need within the voluntary sector." She expressed her satisfaction
with the Commission's support for the initiative.
</P>
<P>
A total of three million ECUs (about 3.5 million U.S. dollars)
has been designated to the initiative, the Commission said in a
statement Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the initiative is to contribute to the work of
non-governmental organizations (NGOs) in combating violence
against children and women.
</P>
<P>
The list of projects covers all EU member states and local,
national as well as EU-wide projects.
</P>
<P>
Among the many different areas of activity are networks for
experts dealing with missing children, a feasibility study of a
register for tracking convicted child sex abusers and an audit of
the provisions for child protection in the EU.
</P>
<P>
Other examples are projects against child pornography on the
Internet, training of police in dealing with women victims of
rape, and projects against exploitation of immigrant women and of
domestic workers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
