<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambican Veterans Demands Better Treatment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The Mozambican Association of
Demobilized Soldiers (AMODEG) today demanded to meet with
President Joaquim Chissano on improving the welfare of its
100,000 members.
</P>
<P>
AMODEG Chairman Julio Nimuire made the call at the opening
ceremony of the Veterans' Week, an event designed to mark
AMODEG's sixth anniversary.
</P>
<P>
Nimuire also expressed the wish to meet with Afonso Dhlakama,
Chairman of Mozambique's largest opposition party, the National
Resistance Movement of Mozambique (RENAMO), whose retired
soldiers are also among AMODEG members.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is aimed at finding a solution to the difficulties
facing veterans, Nimuire said, adding that it should take place
in central or northern Mozambique next year.
</P>
<P>
"The situation is very bad. We will not exclude the
possibility of a general strike to protect veterans' interest,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Nimuire gave the example of Niassa Province in the north,
where some veterans have to walk 300 kilometers to get their
monthly pension of less than nine U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that the situation in other provinces is actually
the same. 
</P>
</TEXT>
