<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania, Uganda to Jointly Combat Banditry in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania and Uganda
have agreed to jointly battle against banditry in the border
areas and tighten control of the movement of refugees.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was made during a meeting held last week at
Rakai town of Uganda, Tanzania's Buboka District Commissioner
Pius Mlowe told reporters in Buboka on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Mlowe, who attended the two-day meeting, said the delegates
stressed the need of thorough check of identity cards of both
Tanzanians and Ugandans when they try to cross the border, in an
effort to control illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
The delegates agreed that a joint operation between the two
countries would be launched to curb drug traffickers, bandits and
illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
The meeting decided that Ugandan village executive officers
and local government officials will have a mandate to issue local
travel documents for short distance cross-border trips.
</P>
<P>
To curb the theft of cattle, the meeting agreed that domestic
animals will be branded by local authorities in both countries
for easier identification.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania currently provides shelter for 800,000 refugees
coming from Uganda, Rwanda, Burundi, Democratic Republic of
Congo, Somalia and other African countries.
</P>
<P>
Last month the Tanzanian government ordered refugees not to
move out of camps as a measure to tighten security of the
surroundings. Some unlawful refugees have reportedly hijacked
buses, robbing and even killing passengers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
