<HEADLINE> Turkey, Israel to Jointly Produce Arrow Missiles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Turkey and Israel are planning
to jointly produce 500-kilometer-range Arrow missiles, the
Anatolia News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The production of the Arrow missiles is aimed at dealing with
the "growing missile threats" from Iran and Syria, the agency
quoted senior Turkish defense sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made Monday at a meeting held here between
Cevik Bir, Turkish Deputy Chief of General Staff, and David Ivry,
Israeli chief assistant of the defense minister, the news agency
said.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, the two sides evaluated possible threats from
Iran, Syria and Iraq against Turkey and Israel, and discussed the
countermeasures.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has accused Iran and Syria of supporting its outlawed
Kurdish Workers' Party, which has been fighting a war since 1984
in an attempt to establish an independent Kurdish state in eastern
and southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Iran, Iraq and Syria have strongly criticized Turkey
for its close military cooperation with the Jewish state, accusing
Ankara of betraying the interests of the Muslim world.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Israel signed several accords last year on training
military staff and cooperation in defense industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
