<BODY>
<HEADLINE> American Charged With Spying to Leave Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The American citizen,
Richard Bliss, who was arrested and charged with espionage in
Russia, will be allowed to leave under an agreement with the
Russian security service, the U.S. State Department said today.
</P>
<P>
"We understand that Mr. Bliss may depart Rostov-on-Don, Russia,
today on a Qualcomm chartered aircraft for the United States,"
James Foley, a spokesman for the State Department said.
</P>
<P>
"We understand that there was an agreement concluded under
which Mr. Bliss will depart, that was concluded between Mr. Bliss,
Qualcomm, and the Russian security services," he added.
</P>
<P>
Bliss, a 29-year-old employee of Qualcomm Corp, was arrested in
the southern Russian city of Rostov-on-Don on November 25.
</P>
<P>
He was formally charged with espionage, a charge which can
carry a jail term of up to 20 years. He was set free on bail but
not allowed to leave the area of his arrest.
</P>
<P>
He was accused of gathering secret information while performing
surveillance work using satellite equipment in Southern Russia.
</P>
<P>
Bliss, his company and U.S. officials have all denied that he
was spying. They said he was using standard land-surveying
equipment as part of his work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
