<HEADLINE> Security Concept Says Russia Threatened by </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The Russia's National Security
Concept ratified recently stated that Russia's security is
threatened now, and will be threatened in the foreseeable future,
by nonmilitary forces, the Interfax reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The concept says the nonmilitary forces are chiefly internal.
Most of them are concentrated in the internal political, economic,
social and spiritual spheres.
</P>
<P>
The country's economic crisis is said to pose the most
dangerous threat to national security. The low level of
large-scale investments in the Russian economy poses a special
threat.
</P>
<P>
The concept noted that threats are also felt through attempts
by other countries to obstruct the consolidation of Russia as an
influential center of the emerging multipolar world.
</P>
<P>
It says Russia's influence on the solution of key international
issues which have a bearing on its interests has significantly
decreased. The creation of a comprehensive European security model
on principles largely developed by Russia has run into problems.
</P>
<P>
On the NATO eastward expansion, the concept says it is
unacceptable for it threatens Russia's security.
</P>
<P>
The concept emphasizes Russia gives preference to political
economic and other nonmilitary tools to prevent wars and armed
conflicts. At the same time Russia must maintain a military force
sufficient for its defense.
</P>
<P>
According to Russian Security Council press service, the
concept consists of a preamble and four parts.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin signed a decree approving the
national security concept on December 18. 
</P>
</TEXT>
