<HEADLINE> Chinese President Visits State-Owned Enterprises (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Without reforms, the state-owned enterprises would not be able
to meet the requirements in developing socialist market economy
and would not be able to play greater role as the pillar of the
national economy," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The temporary difficulties encountered by some state-owned
enterprises are inevitable in the process of continuous reforms,"
he noted, "And we are taking active measures to address these
problems."
</P>
<P>
Speaking about the reemployment and the livelihood of the
workers from the bloated state-owned enterprises and the laid-off
workers, he stressed that whatever is concerned with the
production, life and immediate interests of people should be
given top priority for consideration.
</P>
<P>
"Leading officials must heed politics and the politics
fundamentally means their attitude towards the people," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Officials at all levels, particularly the leading officials,
must always be concerned with the well-being of the masses," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese president pointed out that at present, greater
efforts must be made to help the laid-off workers to get
re-employed as soon as possible and ensure basic means of
living for the poor workers and the retirees.
</P>
<P>
"Efforts should be speeded up to set up and improve the basic
social security system of the urban residents and the basic
pension system of the enterprise employees," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Leading officials at all levels must follow the policy of
building the country through thrift and hard work and oppose
extravagance and waste," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We must do our best to cut the unnecessary financial expenses
and support the reform and development of the state-owned
enterprises," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to the enterprises, the Chinese president
extended his warm festival greetings to the workers and the
enterprise leaders as the New Year and the traditional Spring
Festival are approaching..
</P>
<P>
Accompanied by Beijing mayor Jia Qinglin and other senior
Chinese officials, Jiang also called on two workers' families.
</P>
</TEXT>
