<HEADLINE> Pak PM Urges Promotion of Trade With Saudi Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif said here Wednesday that the fraternal ties between
his country and Saudi Arabia need to be translated into further
trade and business relations.
</P>
<P>
The present trade volume between Pakistan and Saudi Arabia
"does not reflect the magnitude of relationship between the two
countries," said Sharif while meeting with a visiting Saudi
delegation led by Commerce Minister Osama Faqih Jaffar, the
Associated Press of Pakistan said.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Sharif briefed the delegation on the
economic reform packages adopted by his government.
</P>
<P>
There has been a major improvement in the investment climate in
Pakistan due to its liberal investment and privatization policies,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Osama appreciated the bold and investment-friendly policies of
the Pakistani government, and expressed the confidence that Saudi
investors would take advantage of the opportunities being offered
by the government of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Osama called on Pakistani Commerce Minister
Ishaq Dar and discussed with him a wide range of issues on
promoting bilateral trade.
</P>
<P>
"We need exploration of all possible avenues to increase the
quantum of trade between the two countries," Dar said.
</P>
<P>
He also spoke of the immense potential of Pakistan's
agriculture sector and stressed the need of close cooperation
between the private sectors of both countries in this field.
</P>
<P>
Osama expressed the hope that the private sectors would play a
key role in boosting trade and business between the two brotherly
countries.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed his satisfaction with Pakistani-Saudi joint
ventures and emphasized the need for setting up more mutually
beneficial joint ventures.
</P>
<P>
Osama Wednesday also discussed with Pakistani Petroleum and
Natural Resources Minister Nisar Ali Khan ways and means to boost
the trade of petroleum products between the two countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
