<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Snowstorms Cause Serious Disaster in Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAGQU, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Heavy snowfalls in the middle of
December have intensified the disaster in snowstorm-hit Nagqu
Prefecture, a major pastoral area in southwest China's Tibet
Autonomous Region, but no deaths of people were reported thanks to
the government's disaster-relief efforts.
</P>
<P>
About 260,000 people and five million heads of livestocks are
suffering from the disaster in 110 townships, where the snowfall
is 40 cm on average. In some heavily-stricken villages, the
snowfall has reached above 50 cm.
</P>
<P>
Experts said the snowfalls came more than 50 days earlier than
the same period last year, and the average minimum temperature for
the prefecture is now 30 degrees Celsius below zero. Some 78,000
head of livestock have already died from the low temperature.
</P>
<P>
The regional government has cleared snows from the blocked
highways and transported disaster-relief goods to the area. A loan
of some 22 million yuan (about 2.65 million US dollars) has also
been provided for purchasing livestock from farmers as a way of
reducing their losses. Besides, telecommunication lines and
equipment damaged by the heavy snowfalls were repaired promptly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
