<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President Visits State-Owned Enterprises (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 24 (Xinhua) -- In the freezing winter morning
of today, Chinese president Jiang Zemin visited state-owned
businesses and workers' families in Beijing, pledging more
financial support to the reform and development of state-owned
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
"The great majority of the workers of the state-owned
enterprises have for a long time made huge contributions to the
country's economic development and social progress," he told
executives of the Beijing North Engine Plant, the Beijing February
7 Locomotive Plant, the Beijing Electronic Information Corporation
and the Beijing Switchgear Plant.
</P>
<P>
"The temporary lay-off of workers and the consequent
difficulties have been caused chiefly by the changes of domestic
and overseas markets as well as by the readjustment of the economic
and industrial structures," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The leading officials at all levels, particularly the high and
middle-ranking officials, must have stronger sense of
responsibility and must work day and night to help solve the
problems of wokers in difficult enterprises and the laid-off
workers," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Any Party and government official who ignores the problems are
completely derelict of their duty," he said.
</P>
<P>
Beijing North Engine Plant, a large enterprise which lost 33.57
million yuan in the early 1990s and is expected to make a profit
of 10 million yuan this year, currently has laid off 300 workers.
</P>
<P>
Beijing February 7 Locomotive Plant, which has a history of 100
years, has encountered difficulties in restructuring and has laid
off 600 workers.
</P>
<P>
"The state-owned enterprises, particularly the large and
medium-sized enterprises, being the backbone, leading force and
pillar of the national economy, have made huge contributions to
the national economic construction and the built-up of the
national defense," he said.
</P>
<P>
"But in the meantime, we must realize that the state-owned
enterprises need to experience a deep process of reform under the
conditions of opening up to the outside world and the socialist
market economy," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
