<HEADLINE> Malaysia Quits from Tour of South China Sea Cycling Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Defending champion Malaysia
decided to quit the Second Tour of South China Sea Cycling Race
starting here this weekend, according to the Hong Kong Cycling
Association (HKCA) on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
HKCA did not explain the reasons for Thailand's withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
The change cut the participating teams to 10 from six
countries and regions, including three from China's mainland, two
each from Macao and Hong Kong and one each from Chinese Taipei,
Mongolia and Japan.
</P>
<P>
The six-race, 426-kilometer tour starts in Hong Kong with two
races set for Saturday and Sunday, both in the northern part of
the "New Territories".
</P>
<P>
The tour then moves to the Southern Chinese city of Zhuhai, for
two races on Monday and Tuesday. The final two races are set for
next Wednesday and Thursday, both in Macao.
</P>
<P>
The inaugural Tour of South China Sea Race was held last
December, with five races staged in Hong Kong, Zhuhai and Macao.
</P>
</TEXT>
