<DOCNO> XIE19971224.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Humanitarian Aid Stalled by Customs Barriers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Humanitarian aid to Ukraine has
decreased by more than half in 1997 as foreign donors are
frustrated by customs delays and import duties.
</P>
<P>
Aid volumes that had climbed steadily for years peaked at
50,000 tons in 1996. This year, the total is down to just 20,000
tons, said Bronislav Ometsynsky, deputy head of the Ukrainian
government's Humanitarian Aid Commission.
</P>
<P>
"Of course aid is shrinking if it cannot get into the country,"
said Onno Elderenbosch, counselor at the embassy of the
Netherlands, the third-largest donor of humanitarian aid to
Ukraine after the United States and Germany.
</P>
<P>
Ometsynsky acknowledged that complicated customs clearance
procedures and constant changes in tax rules have deprived Ukraine
of badly needed clothing, food and medicine. There have been at
least six changes in the government's policy on exempting
humanitarian aid from taxes and import duties since 1996.
</P>
<P>
First, a cabinet decree exempting humanitarian aid from taxes
was canceled in November 1996. Then the tax exemptions were
restored in February, but only for aid donors approved in advance
by the Humanitarian Aid Commission.
</P>
<P>
Second, a duty on imported foodstuffs imposed on October 7
subjected humanitarian food shipments to tariffs averaging 30
percent. On October 31, aid donors were subjected to a 20 percent
value-added tax on their shipments.
</P>
<P>
"Of course, all this damaged our country's image and cost us
30,000 tons of humanitarian aid," said Ometsynsky.
</P>
<P>
Besides, customs delays have also drawn loud complaints from
aid donors. Elderenbosch said that many private donor
organizations in the Netherlands have simply bypassed Ukraine
after encountering problems here.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the U.S. government has reduced humanitarian
assistance. This year, it sent supplies worth 35 million dollars,
down from 50 million dollars last year and 80 million dollars in
1995, Ometsynsky added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
