<HEADLINE> Mugabe Names Members of Health Review Commission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe today swore in nine members of an independent review
commission on health to look into the country's ailing health
sector.
</P>
<P>
The commission, which includes a panel of five doctors, will
be chaired by a Tanzanian national, Eleuthera Tarimo, who is
currently working with the World Health Organization (WHO).
</P>
<P>
Tarimo retires from the WHO at the end of this month to take
up the chairmanship of the commission full time.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after the swearing-in ceremony, Health
and Child Welfare Minister Timothy Stamps said the commission,
set up against the background of decreased funding to the health
sector, will also be tasked to look into the impact of chronic
diseases such as diabetes, HIV/AIDS, heart diseases, tuberculosis
and new strains of cancer.
</P>
<P>
''The commission will generally look at the health system in
overall and how effective it is in discharging its duties and
providing health services and to see where we can improve,'' the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
The commission is expected to report back to the president at
the end of March next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
