<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Environmental Experts Call for Fewer Greeting Cards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese environmentalists have
called on their countrymen to mail fewer greeting cards to save
forests and reduce pollution.
</P>
<P>
The appeal was made just ahead of the peak New Year season when
Chinese people mail hundreds of millions of cards to convey
festive greetings.
</P>
<P>
"Few people know that producing 4,000 cards may consume one
tree, or more than 250,000 trees will be felled if about one
billion cards are made around the world annually," said Zhang
Mingxu of the Shanghai Municipal Research Institute of
Environmental Science.
</P>
<P>
The production of greeting card paper also threatens the
environment when paper-making enterprises, especially small mills
lacking disposal facilities, discharge untreated wastewater into
rivers, Zhang was quoted in the "Yangcheng Evening News."
</P>
<P>
China's task is particularly tough because of little awareness
of environmental protection in some enterprises, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
One place where awareness may be growing is Shanghai, China's
most fashionable metropolis, where the sales of greeting cards
were reportedly down this winter compared with previous years.
</P>
<P>
"Recently, delivery amount of the cards isn't as high as the
same periods of the previous two years," Shen Rongchang, an
official with the Shanghai Post Office, told "Jiefang Daily."
</P>
<P>
Salespersons at a department store also said the card business
is not as brisk as in past years, even though there are more than
100 varieties available. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
