<HEADLINE> Alleged Terrorists on Trials in Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 24 (Xinhua) -- The Federal High Court is
carrying out the trials of 14 individuals charged with killing of
civilians and damaging properties in various parts of the
country, Ethiopia's Public Prosecutor Office said here today.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopian News Agency said the alleged individuals are members
of the terrorist organization, Al-Itihad, which are involved in
the killings and injurings of civilians, properties damages with
bombings and gun fires in their bid to distort the existing
peaceful situation in Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
The charges say 11 of the defendants who entered Ethiopia
illegally from Somalia along with accomplices still at large are
responsible for the bombings at Ghion Hotel and Wabe Shebelle
Hotel in Addis Ababa, and Ras Hotel in Dire Dawa, second largest
city in Ethiopia, in which several civilians lost their lives.
</P>
<P>
They are also the ones who planted an explosive in a passenger
bus on its way to Mekele, capital city of northern Tigray region,
in early July two years ago and caused the dreaded deaths of the
travelers including four children, the charges by the prosecutor
office unveil.
</P>
<P>
Among the crimes the defendants committed at various times is
the assassination attempt on Abdulmejid Hussien, Ethiopia's
Minister of Transport and Communication, in July last year in
Addis Ababa.
</P>
<P>
Three of the alleged individuals are being tried for making
money and material supports to the terrorists, according to the
prosecutor office. 
</P>
</TEXT>
