<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Draft of Blood Donation Law Submitted for Approval </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 24 (Xinhua) -- The draft of a law on blood
donation was submitted today to the 29th session of the Standing
Committee of the Eighth National People's Congress (NPC) which
opened here.
</P>
<P>
The draft has been deliberated twice at previous NPC Standing
Committee sessions, during which many committee members suggested
revisions.
</P>
<P>
After the deliberations, the Bureau of Legislative Affairs
under the State Council and the Ministry of Health pored over the
proposed revisions and added new articles to encourage citizens to
voluntarily donate blood, and new articles to protect the health
of both donors and recipients.
</P>
<P>
Explaining the draft to China's top legislative body, Chen
Minzhang, minister of health, said early last month that a
voluntary blood-donation mechanism should be established to ensure
blood quality.
</P>
<P>
"Blood donation embodies mutual assistance and unselfish
dedication. Neither blood donors nor donation organizers should be
motivated by money," Chen said, adding that "the Chinese
government has been opposing blood sales."
</P>
<P>
When the significance and physiological knowledge on donations
are publicized and sales are checked, Chen said, the demand for
clinical blood can be met and pollution avoided.
</P>
<P>
According to the draft, the state advocates voluntary blood
donations by healthy citizens between 18 and 55, who in turn will
be given certificates issued by health departments and will obtain
a subsidy from employers.
</P>
<P>
The proposed law would prohibit centers from collecting blood
from the same donor too frequently. Those blood center workers who
violate collection regulations would be severely punished. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971224.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
