<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China To Speed Up Housing Reform in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, December 24 (Xinhua) -- China will step up efforts in
1998 to change the present system of housing distribution as a
welfare to the people, according to an ongoing national conference
on economic restructuring.
</P>
<P>
What needs to be solved now in reforming the housing system is
to persuade urban residents to be willing to buy housing and
enable those low- and middle-income families to be able to afford
their housing.
</P>
<P>
Official sources say that measures to speed up the housing
reform include:
</P>
<P>
-- The housing investment by the state, businesses and
government institutions will be gradually incorporated into the
wages of the workers and government functionaries, turning the
housing fund into allowances for them to buy their own housing;
</P>
<P>
-- The rise of housing rent will be speeded up in line with the
percentage the housing rent accounts in the wages of the husband
and wife, thus accelerating the transition from housing rent to
housing cost rent;
</P>
<P>
-- Housing will be gradually sold at cost prices;
</P>
<P>
-- The system of the housing public accumulation funds will
continue and the credit loans for housing purchasers will be
encouraged;
</P>
<P>
-- Housing mortgage loans for individuals will be increased; and
</P>
<P>
-- Efforts will be made to promote the marketing of the housing
with total property right.
</P>
<P>
At present, majority of the urban houses in China are built by
the state, businesses or government institutions and then are
distributed to the workers and government officials and employees
according to their standing or seniority.
</P>
<P>
China will decide in a given period of time to allow no
businesses or government institutions to build housing for their
workers and employees. The existing houses will be gradually sold
to the enterprise workers and government officials and employees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
