<HEADLINE> Iran Welcomes Rabbani's Pakistani Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Iran regards Pakistan's
inviting ousted Afghan President Burhanuddin Rabbani to visit
Islamabad as a positive step towards reducing tensions in
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Iran's representative on Afghan affairs
Alaeddin Boroujerdi. "I hope the trip will create an understanding
between Taliban and the Rabbani government," Iran's official news
agency IRNA quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Rabbani held meetings today in Islamabad
with Pakistani leaders with the aim to end the civil war in
Afghanistan. He paid the visit to Pakistan at the invitation of
Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif.
</P>
<P>
Islamabad has been supporting Taliban, the religious students'
army which took over capital Kabul and drove out the Rabbani
government more than a year ago. Taliban is accused by Iran for
refusing to join the country's peace process.
</P>
<P>
Reaffirming support to the Rabbani government, Iran has tried
to bring the warring factions together on a negotiating table by
hosting an Afghan conference early this month.
</P>
<P>
Boroujerdi said that the discussions between Rabbani and Sharif
on the sidelines of the eighth Islamic summit, held in Tehran on
December 9-11, is the beginning of a new policy of Pakistan
towards Rabbani's government.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that Pakistan will use its influence on
the Taliban militia to stop the bloodshed in the war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
He said that Iran will soon send humanitarian assistance to the
deprived Afghan people, hoping other countries will also provide
relief aid to them, especially those in the central parts of the
country.
</P>
<P>
Those people are facing threats of lack of food after the
Taliban militia completed a siege to block the U.N. relief
assistance from reaching the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
