<HEADLINE> Icelandic Aid Plane to Arrive Baghdad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 24 (Xinhua) -- A special Icelandic plane
carrying gifts and medicines to Iraq will arrive in Baghdad
Thursday morning on the occasion of Christmas Day, Iraqi News
Agency (INA) reported today.
</P>
<P>
These gifts are from the "Peace 2000 Institute," an Icelandic
humanitarian organization based in Reykjavik, capital of Iceland,
according to the INA.
</P>
<P>
This direct flight is an expression of the solidarity of the
people of Iceland, as well as people who love justice, peace and
stability all over the world, with the people of Iraq, said INA,
adding that this is a reflection of their rejection of the
seven-year-old U.N. embargo on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Icelandic plane will also carry a delegation representing
the Icelandic humanitarian organization, a female reporter from
Channel 2 of Iceland TV and three members of the "Airlift to
Baghdad" organization of Italy, in addition to a photographer from
the same organization.
</P>
<P>
Another aid plane, chartered by Russia's Liberal Democratic
Party to carry medicines for Iraqi children had been stopped by
Iran.
</P>
<P>
Scheduled to land in Iraq today, the plane was prevented to
enter Iraq through Iran and is currently held up with a delegation
of 20 people at Iran's western city of Kermanshah near the Iraqi
border.
</P>
<P>
The humanitarian aid carried by the plane will be transported
to Iraq by road as Iran thinks that "sending the cargo through air
would only be possible through special U.N. authorization."
</P>
