<HEADLINE> Chinese Filmmakers Consider Challenges From Hollywood (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 24 (Xinhua) -- China's film market, like that
of other developing countries, is facing great challenges from
Hollywood. "How to produce attractive domestic movies" was a topic
of general concern at the recently closed Sixth Golden Rooster and
Hundred Flowers Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
Each year China imports about 10 foreign films, mostly
Hollywood movies. Experts predicted that as China continues
efforts to join the World Trade Organization (WTO), more overseas
films will be screened here. If that happens, the Chinese film
industry could come across more serious difficulties.
</P>
<P>
"Exciting stories, beautifully packaged and successful use of
hi-tech make American films interesting and attractive," say both
viewers and filmmakers.
</P>
<P>
Lu Zhuguo, a famous playwright, agreed that China should learn
from Hollywood and double its efforts to make more attractive
movies.
</P>
<P>
"However, it doesn't mean China may blindly imitate others,"
said Lu, who stressed that Chinese movies should tell about the
lives and stories of its own, because nations have different
cultural traditions, aesthetic conceptions and social values.
</P>
<P>
Chinese artworks, including films, give more attention to
social effects than economic results.
</P>
<P>
Most filmmakers in China had a common understanding that the
rejuvenation of the Chinese film industry should rely on their own
efforts, and that reforms should be deepened in screenplays,
collecting money, marketing operations and personnel training.
</P>
<P>
Yu Min, who wrote New China's first film, called on his
counterparts to closely watch reality and ordinary people's
happiness, sadness or anger, as well as issues of common concern.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
