<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Draft of High-Tech Development Zone Law Submitted for Examination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 24 (Xinhua) -- The draft of state high-tech
development zones law was submitted for the first time to China's
top legislative body for examination today.
</P>
<P>
Li Xu'e, vice-chairman of the Education, Science, Culture and
Public Health Committee of the National People's Congress (NPC),
explained the proposed law at the 29th meeting of the Standing
Committee of the Eighth NPC which opened here today.
</P>
<P>
Li said the aim of drafting the law is to put into effect the
strategy of vitalizing the nation through science and education,
to promote and standardize the construction of state high-tech
development zones and to develop high-tech industries. This would
help China to promote scientific and technological progress,
economic construction and social development.
</P>
<P>
Cities including Beijing, Shenzhen and Wuhan started building
high-tech development zones in the mid-1980s. During the 1991-1992
period, the State Council approved 52 state high-tech development
zones.
</P>
<P>
Statistics for the 1991-1996 period show that the annual
industrial output value of these development zones has increased
at an average rate of 90 percent. In 1996 these zones' total
industrial output value reached 210 billion yuan (25.3 billion
U.S. dollars), their pre-tax profits, 24 billion yuan (2.89
billion U.S. dollars) and their earnings from exports, 3.8
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are more than 900 kinds of high-tech
development zones worldwide, he said.
</P>
<P>
Li said the tasks for state high-tech development zones are to
promote the transfer of Chinese high-tech achievements into
commodities and the industrialization of high-tech findings, based
on China's scientific and technological strength and industrial
basis.
</P>
<P>
Li stressed that enterprises in these development zones must
possess as many intellectual property rights of their own nation
as they can, and make new progress based on imported advanced
technologies.
</P>
<P>
The draft consists of seven chapters in 33 articles.
</P>
<P>
According to the draft, the State Council is responsible for
the macro-control over all the country's development zones, and
governments at lower levels are responsible for the construction
and development of those zones within their own administrative
regions.
</P>
<P>
It also has detailed stipulations on the qualification
recognition of high-tech enterprises in development zones, and the
state's preferential policies on developing high-tech industries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971224.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Filmmakers Consider Challenges From Hollywood  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Directors and playwrights shouldn't just put their eyes on
historical stories, or only show backwardness in China's
development process to pander to some foreigners' curiosity or
novelty seeking." Yu said.
