<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Christmas Becomes Sales Season in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese businessmen have
learned to capitalize on Christmas celebrations to boost their
sales.
</P>
<P>
Large department stores, restaurants and star hotels in the
Chinese capital have brightened their appearance with Christmas
decorations. Banners bearing "Sale" signs on the doorway are
flapping in the winter chill to beckon potential customers.
</P>
<P>
Inside, there are sections for holiday goods such as Christmas
trees and ornaments, greeting cards and specialized gifts.
</P>
<P>
A saleswoman at "Jialefu," a supermarket in the downtown
Chaoyang District, said that each day they can sell out seven to
eight Christmas trees priced between 100 to 300 yuan (about 12 to
35 U.S. dollars). Other Christmas items are also selling well,
she said.
</P>
<P>
"Our customers are mostly Chinese," she said.
</P>
<P>
The Palace Hotel in the downtown Wangfujing area is promoting
its Christmas dinner -- with gift-giving, of course. The highest
price is 560 yuan per person. Other luxurious hotels either are
attracting customers with what they call "revelry parties" or with
art performances and lottery games.
</P>
<P>
However, most foreigners in Beijing are heading
home. U.S.-based Northwest Airlines is reportedly ferrying more
than 300 people back to the United States every day, though among
them are some Chinese seeking to spend an exotic Christmas holiday.
</P>
<P>
For the 40,000-odd Roman Catholics and about 15,000 Christians,
the most important thing is to attend church services. Bishop Fu
Tieshan is going to preside over a midnight Mass at Xuanwumen
Christian church, the oldest in Beijing. He will offer Christmas
greetings and pray for world peace.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has 17 Christian and eight Catholic churches.
</P>
<P>
Not all Beijing residents are ready to embrace the foreign
holiday. "We have enough festivals and holidays of our own. Why go
after the trend?" asked one middle-aged Beijinger. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
