<HEADLINE> S. Leone Military on Alert for Christmas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, December 24 (Xinhua) -- All government military
forces have been put on "red alert" for any attempt to
destabilize the peace and security of the nation over the
Christmas period, a senior official said today.
</P>
<P>
Sierra Leone's army chief of staff, Colonel Sam Williams said
that "we have monitored reports of a pending attack hatched by
Nigerian soldiers in ECOMOG backed by Kamajor militiamen and some
hired mercenary to make Christmas Day a bloody Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We are ready to react militarily to any such attack with
all might to ensure that the free movement of people is not
imposed by enemies of the state."
</P>
<P>
Williams urged the public "to hold no fear over their
safety and to attend social functions to celebrate the
yuletide."
</P>
<P>
"The job of the army is to defend all civilians residing in
the country and we are determined to follow this to the
letter," he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile local journalists reached in the southern city of
Bo, Sierra Leone's second largest city, denied claims by the
leader of the Kamajors, former deputy defense minister in the
ousted civilian government, Hinga Norman that his militiamen
had blocked all main roads leading to Bo.
</P>
<P>
Travelers arriving in the capital this morning have also
disputed the claim, noting that commuter traffic is flowing
smoothly.
</P>
<P>
Norman also claimed in the interview with the clandestine FM
98.1 radio that all areas controlled by Kamajors "are being
turned over to west African peace-keeping troops known as ECOMOG
as part of the deployment program."
</P>
<P>
"We have also mounted a big military operation to dislodge
junta forces along highway check points in the country under
operation Rambo raid," Norman said.
</P>
<P>
Military reports said the first Rambo raid was attempted
Monday at the mile 91 check point leading to the south but
airborne government troops drove the Kamajors into the bush with
aerial bombardment.
</P>
<P>
The Kamajors are also militarily active in about three-tenths
of the country mainly on the fringes of the mining district of
Kono as well as remote villages near the Sierra Leone-Liberian
border in the south. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
