<HEADLINE> Feature: China Determined to Perform Another "Thames Miracle" (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, December 24 (Xinhua) -- China has determined to clean up
the seriously polluted Huaihe River in three years to complete an
environmental miracle by 2000.
</P>
<P>
"It won't be easy," said a water pollution expert in
Beijing. "Only the British have succeeded in controlling river
pollution. It took them more than four decades to transform a foul
Thames River."
</P>
<P>
China has already spent three years in fighting water pollution
in the Huaihe River Valley, which extends 270,000 square
kilometers, an area slightly larger than Great Britain. More than
5 billion yuan (625 million U.S. dollars) has been spent in
addition to large infusions of manpower and material resources.
</P>
<P>
"The country's largest environmental protection project
witnessed remarkable progress this year," said Qu Geping, chairman
of the Environment and Resources Protection Committee under the
National People's Congress, after a recent tour of the valley.
</P>
<P>
He said the water quality at some major monitoring sites has
been much better. "Some even has approached the level of
drinking-water sources," he said.
</P>
<P>
Residents of the Huaihe River Valley -- Henan, Anhui, Jiangsu
and Shandong provinces -- have been confronted with serious water
pollution problems during the past decade, with 2.4 billion tons
of wastewater pumped into the river each year. In many sections,
fish and shrimp have vanished.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971224.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: China Determined to Perform Another "Thames Miracle" (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China currently is trying to ease the river's pollution
problems through strict control of industrial emissions.
</P>
<P>
The government has sent ultimatums to all factories along the
river, demanding that they meet national anti-pollution standards
before Dec. 31 or be shut down.
</P>
<P>
With the deadline drawing near, businessmen have no time to
take a wait-and-see attitude and are expediting pollution control
projects to avoid closure.
</P>
<P>
Some have not hesitated to use circulating funds; others have
sold cars or stopped housing construction for employees to raise
funds. Pollution control has been regarded as a "life project" in
the valley.
</P>
<P>
The world's largest gourmet powder manufacturer, the Lotus
Gourmet Powder Group in central China's Henan Province, has spent
nearly 160 million yuan (20 million U.S. dollars) in pre-treating
wastewater.
</P>
<P>
"The earlier we take action, the better results we may get,"
said the powder group's general manager Li Huaiqing, adding that
it is a road to ruin to refuse to take anti-pollution measures.
</P>
<P>
The latest report from the National Environmental Protection
Agency (NEPA) says that nearly 60 percent of the 1,500-plus major
polluters in the valley, each with more than 100 tons of daily
wastewater emissions, have completed their sewage treatment
projects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
