<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Tighten Control of Computer Security Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Computer security products,
namely to software and hardware to protect the computer's
information data, must be approved by special agencies designated
by the Ministry of Public Security if they are to enter the
Chinese market, according to a newly promulgated regulation.
</P>
<P>
An official with the ministry said that the new regulation,
which became effective Dec. 12, aims to tighten control of
computer security products and safeguard the security functions of
those products.
</P>
<P>
The regulation says that the computer management and
supervision department under the Ministry of Public Security is
responsible for the approval and issuance of licenses for selling
computer security products.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturers of computer security products who have obtained
their licenses should affix a special sign of "sales permission"
which is produced and issued by the Ministry of Public Security.
</P>
<P>
The regulation stresses that no company or individual is
allowed to sell any kind of computer security product without the
"sales permission" sign.
</P>
<P>
The official said the implementation of the regulation will
serve to safeguard the sovereignty of the nation and play an
important role in protecting the rights and interests of computer
users.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has issued a notice calling on public security
bureaus at all levels to strike hard against computer-related
criminal activities in a move to create a favorable environment
for the country's computer industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971224.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: China Determined to Perform Another "Thames Miracle" (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
This year's move, together with last year's closure of nearly
5,000 small businesses in the valley, has reduced the emission of
organic pollutants by 40 percent to 890,000 tons a year.
</P>
<P>
"It means we have achieved the goal of the first phase of the
anti-pollution war in the Huaihe River Valley," said NEPA's
Director Xie Zhenhua.
</P>
<P>
However, he stressed that it still falls far short of the
target to clean up the river.
</P>
<P>
"The river's pollution problem is still serious," Xie said,
pledging that China will "strictly enforce the law" to ensure that
all the businesses along the river meet the national standards at
year's end.
</P>
<P>
Beginning Jan. 1, the anti-pollution war will enter a second
phase in which China will speed up treatment of urban wastewater
while continuing to enhance industrial pollution control efforts.
</P>
<P>
The country will build 47 urban wastewater treatment plants in
the valley by 2000, which is expected to cut the emission of
organic pollutants by another 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
Experts estimate that China will spend nearly 20 billion yuan
(2.5 billion U.S. dollars) to combat Huaihe's pollution during the
1998-2000 period.
</P>
<P>
The Huaihe River Valley, with a population of 150 million, is
one of China's important grain and energy producers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
