<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile: Moi, Kenya's "Big Man" to Win </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Incumbent Kenyan President
Daniel arap Moi, 73 and in power for 19 years, is widely expected
to beat his 14 challengers and win his final five-year term in
Monday's poll.
</P>
<P>
However, there will be a run-off between the top two
candidates if no one receives at least 25 percent of the vote in
at least five of the country's eight provinces -- the only danger
Moi is facing as analysts say.
</P>
<P>
Moi holds the record as the longest serving president, vice
president and member of parliament in the history of Kenya.
</P>
<P>
"Moi is like a giraffe, while others are like ordinary small
animals. When they are busy grazing down there, the giraffe is
seeing very far," said late opposition FORD-Kenya Chairman
Jaramogi Odinga.
</P>
<P>
"Moi is a person who can stand on a tight rope, juggle with 20
balls and still manage a smile when the pressure is on," the
Kenya Times newspaper quoted an authoritative international
magazine as saying.
</P>
<P>
Also described by the western press, Moi is the last of
Africa's "Big Men" who believe that Africans have always had
their own way of dealing with issues and need no advice from
abroad.
</P>
<P>
"Moi has made his own footprints in the sands of time," said
former British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher during her visit
to Kenya in January, 1988.
</P>
<P>
He is also seen as a prominent peace-broker and active
regional cooperation advocate in the Great Lakes region and
eastern Africa -- with his famous Nyato philosophy -- peace, love
and unity.
</P>
<P>
A member of the Tugen sub-group of the minority Kalenjin
ethnic confederation, Moi was born to the first wife of Kimoi
Chebi on September 2, 1924 in Kurieng'ewo village, Sacho, Baringo
district in Rift Valley province.
</P>
<P>
He was the fourth and last child and named Toroitich. After
two years of his birth, his father passed away, and later two of
his brothers also died. Moi was brought up by his mother and
the remaining elder brother.
</P>
<P>
At 10, he walked some 45 kilometers every day to reach
Kabartonjo Africa Inland Mission School, and, after the long walk
home, he helped his mother tending the cattle and goats daily.
</P>
<P>
It was in Kabartonjo that in October 1936, shortly before he
changed schools, Toroitich was baptized into Daniel as a
Christian.
</P>
<P>
First he transferred to another African Inland Mission School
at Kapsabet in 1938 and later to the Government African School,
Kapsabet, where he was the School Football Team Captain.
</P>
<P>
In 1939, Moi took up his first salaried job when he was hired
to drive two head of cattle from Kabarnet to Kapsowar, some 120
km away. The pay was 2.50 Shillings. "I used it to buy a Bible,"
Moi recalled.
</P>
<P>
In 1945, he went to the nearby Kapsabet Teachers Training
College after which he was posted to Kabarnet Intermediate School
as a teacher and became headmaster there in 1948.
</P>
<P>
Moi made his political debut in October, 1955 at the age of 31
when he was nominated as a member of the Legislative Council
which then only included five Africans.
</P>
<P>
The opposition Kenya African Democratic Union (KADU) party was
formed in 1960 and Moi became Chairman.
</P>
<P>
He was appointed Education Minister in the pre-independence
coalition government of 1960/61.
</P>
<P>
When KADU was dissolved in 1964 following a merger with the
Kenya African National Union (KANU) led by late President Jomo
Kenyatta, Moi was appointed Home Affairs Minister.
</P>
<P>
Since January 1967 he was appointed as Kenyatta's vice
president, he had became almost colorless member of the cabinet
who rarely "put a foot wrong," and operated in the deep shadow of
the larger-than-life Kenyatta until August 1978 when Kenyatta
died in Mombasa.
</P>
<P>
Moi succeeded to the presidency peacefully with vows that
he would follow in Kenyatta's footsteps. As an astute chess
master in politics, he included his political foes in his cabinet
and thus quelled their hostility toward him as he built a solid
base.
</P>
<P>
In 1982, an attempted coup led by Kenya Air Force officers was
crushed by forces loyal to Moi in just three hours.
</P>
<P>
Moi bowed reluctantly to pressure from donors and Opposition
groups and introduced multi-party politics in 1991, but bitterly
blaming it for what he perceives to be an upsurge in tribalism,
violence and other social evils.
</P>
<P>
However, he won the first democratic multi-party elections in
December 1992 with 36.8 percent of the vote against seven rivals.
</P>
<P>
Moi is a regular church-goer and is said to start his working
day as early as five in the morning every day.
</P>
<P>
Father of two girls and five boys, he divorced his wife in
1976 and has not remarried. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
