<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Seizes 5.7 Kg of Marijuana Resin at Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Japanese customs officials and
police said Wednesday that they have confiscated about 5.7 kilograms of
marijuana resin from a German man who tried to smuggle the narcotic
through Tokyo's Narita International airport earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
Karl-Heinz Wolf, the drug carrier, was arrested on suspicion of
violating the Cannabis Control Law following his arrival from
Singapore on December 7, when customs inspectors found the resin
hidden in the false bottom of his suitcase.
</P>
<P>
The confiscated resin, with a street value of about 46 million yen
(about 353,846 dollars), is the second largest amout seized at Narita
airport this year.
</P>
<P>
Wolf said he was paid 5,000 dollars to carry the narcotic, which
was handed to him in a suitcase in Singapore, police said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
