<DOCNO> XIE19971224.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Make New Breakthroughs in Enterprise Reform (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A new managerial system should be set up in a bid to let the
investor, manager and staff encourage and supervise over one
another, the official said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the reform of state firms has experienced four
stages of "relaxing government control and giving enterprises more
profits", "contracting", transformation of mechanism, and creation
of a new system.
</P>
<P>
Great achievements have been made in this regard, however,
quite a large number of state companies are still losing money and
indebted, due to the confusion of property rights and
responsibilities, mixing-up of government and enterprise
functions and outdated managerial methods, the lack of an
operational mechanism that is energetic and meets the requirements
of the socialist market economy, Lu noted.
</P>
<P>
Some Chinese economists believe that the restructuring of state
firms in the country has entered into a crucial but difficult
time.
</P>
<P>
On the one hand, most large and medium-sized state companies
are making efforts to survive from the current difficult
situation. On the other hand, these firms have to adopt the modern
enterprise system. The only way-out is to set up a new system, the
experts hold.
</P>
<P>
To ensure a smooth restructuring of state companies, the
government plans to push forwards the macro-economic
restructuring, including restructuring of the investment system,
in order to improve the system macro-economic control.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government plans to accelerate the establishment
and improvement of the social security system and rearrange
laid-offs from state factories through various channels, so as to
create a sound environment for the restructuring of state
enterprises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
