<DOCNO> XIE19971224.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Economy to Maintain Stable Growth Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 24 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese economy is
expected to maintain its appropriate and stable growth next year
with reforms of state-owned enterprises, the financial industry,
housing and government institutions to be carried out on a larger
scale.
</P>
<P>
Qiu Xiaohua, chief economist of the State Statistics Bureau
(SSB), delivered this message in an exclusive interview with
Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
He said the Chinese economy will grow 8-to-10 percent next
year.
</P>
<P>
The economist foresaw no major increases in the retail market
but believed that the housing market will become more active with
government measures to encourage consumption of residential houses.
</P>
<P>
A joint report by SSB and the Chinese Academy of Social
Sciences points out that the Chinese economy will not grow too
fast because China's investment scale will not grow excessively
following the country's persistence in its "relatively tight"
credit policy for fear of accumulating bad debts.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, financial system reforms will strengthen commercial
banks' resistance against the local government's interference,
making it harder for borrowers to obtain money from commercial
banks.
</P>
<P>
Another reason for unwanted faster economic growth is a
prediction by the State Information Center, which is sponsored by
the State Planning Commission, a slowdown could occur in the
country's export growth next year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chinese financial experts forecast that, despite the
recent financial turmoil around the world, the exchange rate of
Renminbi against the U.S. dollar will remain stable.
</P>
<P>
China's rising foreign exchange reserves and stringent control
over foreign currencies will provide a safe haven for the Renminbi
against international speculators, they said.
</P>
<P>
However, most economists are pessimistic about China's domestic
commodities market, saying that the growth rate for the sale of
capital goods will likely dip lower than the growth rate of the
national economy.
</P>
<P>
Economists agree that the reform of state-owned enterprises
will continue to be the most important task for the national
economy in 1998, and that it is the most crucial factor affecting
the performance of the national economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971224.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique's Economy Grows for Five Consecutive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Li Fuxiang)
</P>
<P>
MAPUTO, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Ever since peace dwells in
Mozambique in 1992, the country has witnessed economic growth for
five consecutive years, with domestic gross product this year is
expected to reach 1.7 billion U.S. dollars, a 6.6 percent
increase over last year.
</P>
<P>
Inflation rate dropped from 54.9 percent in 1995 to 17 percent
last year. This year, the rate could be down at seven percent.
</P>
<P>
After remarkable depreciations for the past few years, Metica,
the national currency, was stable last year. Its exchange rate
with the U.S. dollar only depreciated by one percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture and animal husbandry output has grown by 5.9
percent, with grain harvest of over 1.53 million tons, a 11
percent increase over last year. The cotton output has reached
over 70,000 tons, a record high in the country since its
independence.
</P>
<P>
The industrial and fishery outputs also increased by nine
percent, with food and beverage industries growing by more than
30 percent. The rubber and plastics industry, which is of major
importance in the country's industrial structure, has grown by 14
percent.
</P>
<P>
The mining sector, despite its deep slide last year, has a
boost of about 15 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
The economic development should be attributed to political
stability, and measures taken by the government to boost the
economy. Half of the 653 million dollars investments approved by
the government before June went to the industrial and
agriculturial fields.
</P>
<P>
The loan interest for national currency has dropped by 13 to
20 percentage point. The current loan interest rates are between
19 percent to 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
Import volume in the first half of this year has reduced by 17
percent compared with the same period last year. Among them,
imports of food and consumer products have been greatly decreased
which helps to promot domestic production.
</P>
<P>
Reforms on the Customs since last May have also brewed
results, bringing in an average monthly taxes of seven million
dollars for international trade during the first half of this
year, and 10 million dollars monthly taxes for the second half.
</P>
<P>
Starting from 1987, the privatization process in the country
has quicken its pace this year, with 846 out of the 1,254
registered state-run enterprises already privatised. Management
of the enterprises are now improving, with unemployment going
down.
</P>
<P>
At present, capital, unemployment, social security still
remain to be factors affecting the economic development in the
country. However, the prospects for Mozambique's economy are
bright. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971224.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Six Killed in Road Crash in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Six people were confirmed dead
and 17 others seriously injured in an accident on Tuesday near
Lafia, capital of Nasarawa state in central Nigeria, the Daily
Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
Two of the bodies were burnt beyond recognition while the
injured were rushed to hospital, some of whom were said to be in
critical condition.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted witness accounts that a bus was travelling
from the capital Abuja to Akwa Ibom state in the southeast, when
it had a head-on collision with a Peugeot 504 station wagon
plying the local route.
</P>
<P>
A road marshal, Hassan Safana, who led a rescue operation from
the Federal Road Safety Commission, said the accident occurred at
about 10:00 Tuesday morning, according to the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
