<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Continues to Attract Foreign Investment (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 24 (Xinhua) -- China will open further to the
outside world and continue to make use of foreign investment in an
active, rational and efficient manner to help promote the fast and
healthy growth of the economy and the overall social progress.
</P>
<P>
With an eye on the 21st century, the country will focus on
raising the quality and effectiveness of its national economy and
increase its comprehensive strength and competitiveness when
making use of foreign funds.
</P>
<P>
That was the conclusion at a national conference on utilization
of foreign investment, which opened in Beijing on Monday and
closed today. This was the second such meeting China has held
since 1978. The first conference was held in 1983.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang Zemin, Premier Li Peng and Vice-Premier Zhu
Rongji met with participants attending the conference, while
Vice-Premier Li Lanqing made an important speech on the foreign
investment work China will undertake in the forthcoming century.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation Wu Yi gave a
report on absorbing foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
The conference noted that making use of foreign funds for the
reform and modernization drive is an important component part of
Deng Xiaoping Theory and one of the great practices of building a
socialist economy with Chinese characteristics.
</P>
<P>
In less than 20 years, China has made use of more than 360
billion U.S. dollars, including 220 million US dollars in direct
foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that China has for years ranked in first place
in utilizing direct foreign fund among developing nations and the
second place in the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971224.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India, Russia to Discuss Nuclear Power Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 24 (Xinhua)-- An Indian team will go to
Russia next month to finalize the Indo-Russian deal on the supply
of two 1,000-megawatt nuclear reactors for India's Koodankulam
Atomic Power Station in Tamil Nadu, chief engineer of the station
V. Kchaturvedi said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A supplement to the original agreement signed in 1988 will be
sealed during Russian President Boris Yeltsin's visit to India in
January next year, he said.
</P>
<P>
After Yeltsin's visit, a design report of the Koodankulam
project will be prepared which will include basic design, analysis
and preliminary safety analysis reports. Russia's share will be 60
percent credit to be repaid in long term by India, he further
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
