<DOCNO> XIE19971224.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Revised Draft Law n Price Accentuates Market Role </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 24 (Xinhua) -- China is determined to reform
its pricing system. A revised draft law on price, which places
more stress on market forces in price formation, demonstrates that
determination.
</P>
<P>
The second draft of a pricing system law has been submitted for
examination to the country's highest legislative body, the
Standing Committee of the National People's Congress, which began
its 29th meeting here today.
</P>
<P>
The revised draft stipulates that China adopts and will
gradually perfect a price system with market forces playing a
major role.
</P>
<P>
"Prices should be set to reflect market value and the law of
governing the market value. Therefore, prices for most commodities
and services should be left to market regulation; only very few
commodities and services should be subject to prices set by the
government or under government guidance."
</P>
<P>
To minimize government interference, the draft has limited the
scope of government-set prices to those including "very few
commodities that have a vital bearing on the livelihood of the
general public as well as the national economy; some commodities
that are scant in natural resources, commodities that are
naturally monopolized by government such as electricity; major
public utilities and welfare service charges."
</P>
<P>
The revised draft law demands the establishment of a system of
public hearings. When the government wants to adjust prices on
public utilities or welfare service charges, it should solicit
opinions from the general public. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971224.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Year-Ender: State Enterprise Reform Enters Crucial Stage (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the meantime, while accelerating the restructuring of state
companies, greater efforts have to be made to improve the
country's social security system and to deal with the issues of
unemployment and re-employment.
</P>
<P>
The government has made progress in this concern: state factory
laid-offs, numbering millions, have received assistance from the
government-sponsored re-employment programs.
</P>
<P>
According to central government policy, China plans in the
coming three years to push a strategic re-organization of large
state enterprises by setting up large groups in important
industries.
</P>
<P>
The pace of reforming small state firms will also be speeded up
by such methods as re-organization, merger, leasing, contracting,
joint-stock and selling-out.
</P>
<P>
The current difficulties faced by state enterprises are
temporary. No matter how hard it will be, the reform must be
carried through to the end.
</P>
<P>
In the next three years many state companies may survive the
market competition and continue to be the backbone of China's
economic development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
