<DOCNO> XIE19971224.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Continues to Attract Foreign Investment  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The conference analyzed the chances and challenges China faces
in further drawing foreign investment: the swift progress of
science and technology which has infiltrated economic growth; the
growing scope of international capital and funds, while
circulation speed accelerates; how financial internationalization
greatly affects the economy of various countries; how
international direct investment has become a great impetus for
economic globalization; and multi-national companies becoming
important forces for global resources.
</P>
<P>
Based on these circumstances, the conference held that in the
future China should grasp the following aspects in using foreign
investment:
</P>
<P>
-- The scope of using foreign investment should cater to the
overall development requirements of the economy and embody the
extent of the opening-up policy.
</P>
<P>
-- More advanced and applied science and technology should be
attracted to help remove the obstacles in national economic and
social growth.
</P>
<P>
-- A basic balance between international expenditure and
revenue should be maintained with some surplus, while the Renminbi
value should be kept stable to enhance the coordination of foreign
trade, foreign investment, foreign exchange earnings and foreign
debts.
</P>
<P>
To better draw foreign investment in the future, participants
held that the existing foreign-invested enterprises should be
well-managed. And economic zones such as the Pudong New Area in
Shanghai and the Suzhou Industrial Park in east China's Jiangsu
Province should further improve their investment
environment. Other important elements include updating the legal
system, protecting intellectual property rights, and adjusting
relevant policies in a timely way to help promote the opening-up
drive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
