stronger Wednesday as financial market dealers and traders headed
off for the four-day Christmas holiday break.
</P>
<P>
The domestic currency finished at 65.85 U.S. cents, up from
65.28 previously. During a shortened session, the unit traded
between 65.42 and 65.86 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
Traders said the Australian dollar had picked up a little bit
of steam as the investors who held U.S. dollars bought the
currency as part of a round of pre-Christmas book-squaring.
</P>
<P>
Helping to support the currency on the day was an overnight
lift in the gold price. In New York, gold closed at 294.30 U.S.
dollars an ounce, up 3.20 U.S. dollars from the previous close.
Wednesday in Sydney, gold was trading at 294.05 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the foreign exchange market, the Australian dollar closed at
85.56 yen, from 85.20 Tuesday, and at 1.1690 marks, from 1.1629.
 
