<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rise Sharply on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Share prices rose sharply on
the Singapore market as the benchmark Straits Times Industrials
Index increased by 36.65 points to close at 1572.96 points on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that stock prices were higher by 2.4 percent on
buying of index-linked counters in anticipation of more mergers of
foreign and local shares.
</P>
<P>
However, in the broader market, falls outnumbered rises as
Malaysian shares traded here lost ground, they noted.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume shrank to 91.07 million units, valued
at 239.83 million Singapore dollars (143.61 million U.S. dollars).
Declines continued to overwhelm advances by 234 to 78, while 293
other counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore Telecom was the most actively traded counter as
it registered a turnover of 3.43 million units. It was followed by
DairyF which had 3.19 million units traded. Asia Food and Property
was next with 2.88 million shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
Singapore Press Holdings led the gainers of the day as it rose
by 2.3 Singapore dollars to finish at 17.1 dollars. DBS
(Development Bank of Singapore) increased by 70 cents to end at
10.4 Singapore dollars. Singapore Airlines (SIA) 200 gained 65
cents to close at 8.1 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, NBT was the biggest loser as it declined by
1.92 dollars to end at 3.48 Singapore dollars. SPH Foreign fell by
1.3 dollars to close at 20.6 Singapore dollars. DBS Foreign
dropped by 1.2 dollars to finish at 13.8 Singapore dollars.
</P>
