<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Absorbs $502 million of Foreign Investment in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria absorbed 502 million
U.S. dollars of foreign investment in 1997, which is nearly twice
the 1996 figure and 15 times that of 1992, local media reported.
</P>
<P>
Among the foreign investors, Germany ranked first with 261.8
million dollars, accounting for 20.2 percent of the total. It was
followed by Belgium with 251.6 million dollars, the Netherlands,
Britain and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria attributed the increase of foreign investment to the
currency policy introduced by the government last July and the
announcement to allow the country's lev to float with the
U.S. dollar, which generally stablized the country's financial
situation, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Bulgaria also amended its foreign investment law and
put forward a set of policies to encourage overseas investment.
</P>
<P>
According to the government plan between 1998-2005, Bulgaria
is expected to absorb 4.5-5 billion dollars from overseas in the
period of 1998-2003.
</P>
<P>
After that, it will get some 6.4 billion dollars from such
international financial institutions as the International Monetary
Fund, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
