<HEADLINE> Australian Government Commits to Action on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Australian Federal Finance
Minister John Fahey Wednesday promised ministerial action to solve
the so-called millennium bug after an auditor-general's report
found commonwealth agencies were not taking the risk seriously.
</P>
<P>
All ministers had been told that the year 2000 issue was not
simply an information technology problem within their portfolio,
but was a serious management problem, Fahey said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The Australian National Audit Office (ANAO) report would help
raise awareness among both the public and private sector of the
serious consequences of the problem, Fahey said.
</P>
<P>
The millennium bug is expected to cause chaos at the turn of
the century when many computers will be unable to represent the
year 2000 with two digits.
</P>
<P>
Crucial services such as fire alarms, building lifts, medical
imaging systems, lab instruments, radiotherapy equipment and
critical care patient management systems are liable to be hit by
the bug.
</P>
<P>
But ANAO found that the majority of agencies surveyed were not
following a systematic and structured approach to identifying,
ranking and treating the risks.
</P>
<P>
Fahey said the government had strengthened the risk
identification regime since the ANAO surveyed the agencies six
months ago, each was now required to report quarterly on their
progress towards compliance in 2000, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
