<DOCNO> XIE19971224.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 10:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Despite GCC Stand on Iran, Iraq, Differences Remain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait has expressed
welcome to the results of the just-concluded Gulf Cooperation
Council (GCC) summit, especially its calls on Iraq to implement
all relevant U.N. Security Council resolutions.
</P>
<P>
This was sounded at a Kuwaiti cabinet meeting Tuesday night,
which showed mixed feelings toward GCC's desire to better
relations with Iran, and to allow Iraq to come back to the Arab
world after it complies with all U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait, a victim of Iraqi invasion in 1990 which triggered the
Gulf Crisis, insisted on ruling out reconciliation with the Iraqi
regime at the three-day summit last week.
</P>
<P>
It said there should be a "distinction between Arab
reconciliation and reconciliation with the Iraqi regime" and "the
two can never meet."
</P>
<P>
Diplomats here noted that Kuwait's attitude on this issue runs,
to some extent, counter to an appeal made by the Saudi Crown
Prince Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz, in his arrival statement last
Saturday, for the Gulf Arab states to "overcome their painful
past" and abandon "isolationist concepts."
</P>
<P>
The GCC Secretary General Jamil Hujailan, while talking to
reporters on the sidelines of the summit last Sunday, echoed this
call by saying that "this is a common stand of the GCC states."
</P>
<P>
Qatari Foreign Minister Sheikh Hamad Bin Jassem Bin Jabir
Al-Thani also stressed the need that Iraq returns to the Arab
world after its implementation of relevant U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
However, during the past two days, Kuwaiti government officials
categorically ruled out any reconciliation with Baghdad, despite
Kuwait's "great concern over the sufferings of the Iraqi people."
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Information Minister Sheikh Saud Nasser Al-Sabah said
that "Kuwait's wound inflicted by the Iraqi regime and its
treachery is still painful and deep and will only be cured by the
disappearance of the bloody regime in Iraq."
</P>
<P>
"Let us not be driven by sentiments and let us be firm in
handling the regime in Baghdad," he added.
</P>
<P>
The GCC was founded in 1981 at a time when Iraq and Iran was in
war and groups Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Qatar, Bahrain, the United
Emirates (UAE) and Oman in a political and economic alliance.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, private statements by the GCC states other than the
agreed expressions in the summit's final communique concerning
Iran also give an insight into the marginal differences regarding
improvement process of GCC's ties with Iran.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait, which has been on better terms with Iran, said it is
convinced about the necessity to create a security system for the
Gulf states including Iran, which is a big and powerful country in
the region.
</P>
<P>
While the UAE, which has been locked in a territorial dispute
with Iran over three Gulf islands of Greater and Lesser Tunbs and
Abu Moussa, still expressed reservation about a rapid cooperation
with Iran before the dispute was resolved.
</P>
<P>
The UAE said it has not observed any positive and concrete act
yet by Iran to solve the issue of the islands so far.
</P>
<P>
At the summit, other GCC members reiterated its "full support
to the UAE sovereignty over the islands" now occupied by Iran and
expressed welcome to "any meeting to be concluded between the
leaders of the two countries" that could lead to a settlement of
the dispute.
</P>
<P>
On Iran-GCC relations, Qatar's foreign minister said "they are
distinguished", while Bahraini Emir Sheikh Issa Bin Salman
Al-Khalifa said "I don't think we can talk of any security
partnership (with Iran) unless we overcome all these issues"
including Iran's ongoing occupation of the islands.
</P>
<P>
Despite the differences, the GCC summit did agree to better
relations with Iran and emerge for the first time to take a
coordinating stand on Iraq as the final communique showed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971224.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
