<HEADLINE> India to Develop Vaccine Against AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 24 (Xinhua)-- The Indian government has
decided to develop a vaccine against AIDS which spread fast in the
country, Press Trust of India (PTI) said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
India has lost a 11-year battle to control AIDS with slogans,
condoms and a 100 million U.S. dollar World Bank loan in the past.
More than three million Indians are estimated to have been
infected with human immunodeficiency virus (HIV), making India a
country with the largest number of HIV cases in the world, PTI
said.
</P>
<P>
"There is no alternative. Educational campaigns have not made a
dent and anti-AIDS drugs are not affordable even by rich Indians.
We have the advantage of having skilled people, and with a
concerted national effort, we can make a vaccine," PTI quoted
medical researcher v. Ramalingaswami as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Even if we do not succeed in making a vaccine, it is time for
us to start working on it rather than wait until some one comes
out with a vaccine and asks us to buy it," said Satish Gupta of
the National Institute of Immunology here.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
