<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wu Yi on China's Introduction of Foreign Investment (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Foreign-funded businesses brought competition and the market
mechanism, accelerated the integration of overseas and domestic
markets and promoted the formation and development of China's
markets of capital, labor, technology and information, Wu said.
</P>
<P>
She added that the introduction of advanced technology and
management know-how has spurred adjustments in China's economic
and industrial structures.
</P>
<P>
The advanced technology, equipment and products absorbed by
China as investment have helped to improve technology in such
fields as machine-building, electricity, telecommunications,
automobiles, chemicals, light-industry, textiles, building
materials and food-processing, she said.
</P>
<P>
As a result, many high-tech industries have been rapidly
created and the product-technology gap between China and developed
countries has been greatly shortened, Wu said.
</P>
<P>
She went on to say that foreign investment has also laid a
solid foundation for further escalation of the industrial
structure in China's coastal regions.
</P>
<P>
The introduction of foreign investment has furthered the growth
of China's foreign trade and accelerated the integrity of China's
economy and the world's, she added.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the foreign trade volume of China's foreign-funded
businesses reached 137.1 billion U.S. dollars, more than triple
that in 1992 with an average annual growth of 33.05 percent. The
figure is 47.3 percent of China's total foreign trade in 1996,
compared with 26.43 percent in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Wu also acknowledged that the foreign investment improved
China's balance of foreign exchange because, since 1987,
foreign-funded businesses have maintained a favorable balance of
payment as a whole for 10 years, and the net surplus has increased
year by year.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the payment surplus of foreign-funded businesses
amounted to 11.424 billion U.S. dollars, 40 percent of China's
total, up 90.94 percent over 1995.
</P>
<P>
In the first 10 months of this year, the surplus of businesses
reached 15.119 billion U.S. dollars, 82.27 percent more than the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Wu told the conference that in the last 20 years investment
from Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan accounted for 64.89 percent of
the total overseas investment in China. The investment from these
three regions does not only consolidate their economic ties with
the mainland, but also furthers their economic development.
</P>
<P>
Investments from the United States, Japan, European countries,
the Republic of Korea (ROK) and Singapore also have played an
important role in promoting their economic ties and bilateral
relations with China, the minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
