<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Year-Ender: State Enterprise Reform Enters Crucial Stage (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 24 (Xinhua) -- In 1997 China stepped up
efforts to restructure its state-owned enterprises as more than
3,000 of them went bankrupt or merged, while a number of large
enterprise groups were newly established.
</P>
<P>
The restructuring of state enterprises, which has been regarded
as a key part of the current economic reform, has now entered its
crucial stage.
</P>
<P>
Since late 1978 when China launched its reform, opening and
modernization drive, the reform of state-owned companies has gone
through several stages.
</P>
<P>
Until 1982 state firms had mainly tried to gain greater
decision-making rights for their internal affairs. Between 1983-86
state companies practiced various systems of responsibility. In
the 1987-92 period state firms worked hard to improve their
management and deepen the reform.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993 the reform has focused on transforming the mechanism
of state enterprises and adopting the modern enterprise system.
</P>
<P>
The 512 key firms, which account for 1 percent of state-owned
enterprises in the country, boast 55 percent of the total assets,
60 percent of sales and 85 percent of pre-tax profits. Meanwhile,
a large number of state firms have sailed into troubled
waters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971224.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Govt Said to Be Shocked at Coup Plot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 24 (Xinhua) -- The initial feeling of the
Nigerian government was that of a shock over Sunday's foiled coup
plot involving the country's number two person Chief of General
Staff Oladipo Diya, a close aide to the head of state said on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"In terms of expectations, there was a general expression of
shock," said Chief David Attah, Chief Press Secretary for the
head of state, quoted by press reports today.
</P>
<P>
However everybody is beginning to recover, Attah said shortly
after the opening of a meeting of the Provisional Ruling Council
(PRC), the nation's highest policy making body, of which Diya was
the sole vice-chairman, last night in the capital Abuja.
</P>
<P>
PRC members, mostly senior military officers, began their
meeting at about 8:00 last night to deliberate on the botched
alleged coup and assess the general security situation and the
prop?d 1998 budget.
</P>
<P>
According to Attah, preliminary investigations are still on
and more information on the progress made so far will be made
public as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
But the newly-sworn in Mnister of Information and Culture,
Chief Ikeobasi Mokelu, noted that the government has to take time
to provide informtion about the aborted coup because of the
nature of the plot and it did not want to compromise national
security.
</P>
<P>
"We must not allow undue haste to supply information either to
compromise vital interests or lead to miscarriage of justice," he
said in Abuja.
</P>
<P>
The minister promised that he will supply "timely and
adequate" information that will be "truthful, credible and
impartial".
</P>
<P>
In Lagos, defense spokesman Godwin Ugbo also appealed
Nigerians and the international community to "waiting for the
outcome of investigation into the attempted overthrow".
</P>
<P>
According to Ugbo, it took three months for people to start to
believe that there was indeed a coup plot when a coup attempt was
announced by the defense headquarters in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Like the situation in 1995 coup plot, which involved former
Head of wState Olusegun Obasanjo and his deputy Sheghu Musas
Yar'adua, anyone who was cleared would be released after a
thorough investigation to determine the level of involvement of
the persons arrested, he added.
</P>
<P>
Altogether 12 people, including Diya, two other generals, four
colonels and one lt.-colonel, were arrested in the coup plot
uncovered last Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
