<DOCNO> XIE19971224.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Faces Challenges in Developing Accounting Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 24 (Xinhua) -- China's public accounting
market faces both opportunities and challenges, a senior industry
official said today.
</P>
<P>
"The establishment and improvement of a socialist market
economic structure have created a good environment and favorable
conditions for the development of the country's accounting
industry," Cui Jianmin, president of the Chinese Association of
Certified Public Accountants (CACPA), said at a national meeting
of his association.
</P>
<P>
The development of a market economy, reforms of the state-owned
enterprises and implementation of a system requiring the annual
accounting sheets of enterprises to be audited by CPAs will
combine to create a huge market for accounting services, Cui said.
</P>
<P>
He said that China's public accounting industry has experienced
rapid growth in the last 18 years. Official figures indicate that
China currently has 133,000 CPAs and 6,900 accountants' offices.
</P>
<P>
However, the current status of China's public accounting
industry is far from adequate to meet the need of developing a
market economy in the country, Cui said.
</P>
<P>
Most of China's accounting offices are too small and some
accountants and accounting offices have failed to demonstrate
sufficient legal, risk and self-discipline awareness, he said.
</P>
<P>
Increasingly fierce competition from overseas firms has posed a
serious challenge to China's public accounting industry, according
to Cui.
</P>
<P>
Many of the largest accounting firms in the world have
established their presence in China. The cooperative offices of
the world's six largest accounting firms, including Earnst &AMP;
Young, account for less than 0.1 percent of the total number of
accounting firms in China, but 10 percent of the Chinese market.
</P>
<P>
While China is opening its accounting market, it will also
formulate and implement effective measures to help sharpen the
competitive edge of its accounting firms, Cui said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971224.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Year-Ender: State Enterprise Reform Enters Crucial Stage (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The average debt rate for China's state enterprises has
exceeded 65 percent, and more than 20 percent of the firms have
ceased operations, completely or partially. Thousands of small
state companies have been sold and leased out, or merged with
others.
</P>
<P>
To date, the country's registered unemployment in urban areas
has surpassed 3 percent as six million workers have been laid off
from state factories.
</P>
<P>
The current difficult situation of the state sector has been
caused by poor management, the changing of a seller's market into
a buyer's market, the heavy historical burdens as well as the
long-time confusion between the functions of the government and
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The main tasks remaining are to transform the function and
mechanism of state enterprises, and to rebuild the relationship
between state firms and the government, customers, banks and
enterprises of other ownerships.
</P>
<P>
State-enterprise reform not only relies on the companies' own
efforts, but also on improvement in the external environment,
especially the reform of government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
