<DOCNO> XIE19971224.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Banks Start Fixing Millennium Bug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 24 (Xinhua) -- A large Thai commercial bank
believes that over 70 percent of its 4,400 computer software
programs used in its operations will be affected by the date
change in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The Siam Commercial Bank has spent the last 15 months examining
its computer programs and is now working on modifying over 2.7
million lines of computer code, according to a Bangkok Post report
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Problems will occur in software when the two digit number for
the year 2000 (y2k) becomes '00'. In addition, the year 1999 will
also cause problems, as dates such as 1/1/99 and 9/9/99 are often
used by programmers to indicate an exceptional situation. Thus,
when these dates are entered in a database, unexpected things may
happen.
</P>
<P>
No business will be unaffected by the y2k impact and banks tend
to be more affected in two years' time, unless problem codes are
modified, the newspaper quotes specialists as warning.
</P>
<P>
However, the real threat the y2k problem poses may lie in
hazards from weapon systems, munitions depots, nuclear plants and
medical systems, where an error can be fatal.
</P>
<P>
Somchai Chilayon, a Microsoft consulting services manager, even
cautioned that when the new year comes around in two years' time,
do not fly in any aircraft, or take a boat or even an elevator.
</P>
<P>
Since all companies which have computer systems will have to
face this problem, some specialists call it a national issue and
urge government agencies to address it.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
