<HEADLINE> Stocks Rebound in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Tokyo Stocks rebounded Wednesday
for the first time in four trading days this week following a
recovery in several international blue chips.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei average of 225 selected issues on the First Section of
the Tokyo Stock Exchange ended at 14,924.98, up 125.58 points, or
0.85 percent, from Monday's close.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
issues on the First Section, rose 4.59 points, or 0.41 percent, to
1,134.59.
</P>
<P>
Share prices bounced back for the first time after a major
1700-point loss over the previous three trading days.
</P>
<P>
Volume on the First Section came to an estimated 550 million
shares, down from Monday's 676.69 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Collapsed Yamaichi Securities Co. was today's most actively
traded issue.
</P>
<P>
The drop in bank issues slowed after the midmorning announcement
that the ruling Liberal Democratic Party and its two noncabinet
allies had decided to endorse a 13 trillion yen (about 100 billion
dollars) bank recapitalization plan.
</P>
<P>
While bank issues remained weak, high-tech, electrical and
automobile blue chips rose in the afternoon, leading the benchmark
Nikkei to briefly top the 15,000 mark.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,327 issues listed on the First Section, losers outpaced
gainers 671 to 497 with 125 issues unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
