<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Exports Up 19.8 Percent in First 10 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's exports grew 19.8
percent in the first 10 months this year, reaching 1.3 trillion
baht, thanks largely to the plunging value of the baht.
</P>
<P>
However, in terms of U.S. dollars, the export value for the
period rose only by 4.4 percent, to 48 billion dollars, based on
an average exchange rate of 27 baht to the dollar, according to
the commerce ministry figures available Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
During the 10-month period and in baht terms, industrial
exports grew 18.4 percent, agribusiness exports increased 10.9
percent, and agricultural exports raised 4.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, imports during the 10 months dropped by 10.1 percent
in dollar terms, with imports of vehicles and auto parts declined
and fuel, capital products, raw and semi-finished materials
increased.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the country's trade account was 53.6 percent lower
than the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The ministry forecast that exports for the entire year would
expand by 3.5 percent in dollars, and by 26 percent in baht.
</P>
<P>
Although the weaker baht has helped exports dramatically by
making them cheaper, the positive impact would last only two
years, the ministry said. It urged producers and exporters to
improve product quality and competitiveness.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
