<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Stock Market Remains Weak This Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 24 (Xinhua) - Hong Kong's stock market
remained weak in the week amid a regional financial crisis which
has showed no signs of settling down.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Hang Seng Index lost 63.37 points or 0.6 percent
to finish the holiday-shortened week to Wednesday at 10,342.44.
</P>
<P>
Trading day-to-day depends on what's going on in other markets,
particularly Tokyo and Seoul which are embroiled in financial
woes, said dealers.
</P>
<P>
The value of turnover was very thin with investors standing on
the sidelines. For the three-day trading week, 14.159 billion Hong
Kong dollars (1.82 billion U.S. dollars) worth of shares changed
hands, compared with 35.976 billion HK dollars (4.61 billion
U.S. dollars) for the previous five-day trading week.
</P>
<P>
Following a 2.0 percent drop in the previous week, the market
was off to a bearish start Monday with the blue-chip index losing
233.34 points or 2.24 percent to 10,172.47 on the heel of a
decline on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
The index gained 195.63 points, or 1.92 percent, to close at
10,368.10 Tuesday as markets in New York and Tokyo rebounded.
</P>
<P>
In the half-day trading of Wednesday the market edged down
25.86 points, or 0.25 percent.
</P>
<P>
The market is closed Thursday and Friday for Christmas,
followed by the regular week-end break.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
