<HEADLINE> North Bangladesh Rich in Coal Reserves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 24 (Xinhua) -- The northern part of Bangladesh
is rich in coal reserves, press reports quoted Bangladeshi
geological experts as saying recently.
</P>
<P>
The northern region of the country was virtually floating on
coal, said Director General of Bangladesh Geological Survey
Khurshid Alam, referring to geological surveys carried out in
Jamalganj, Barapukuria, Khalashpir, Dihipara and Fulbaria, in the
districts of Jaipurbat, Dinajpur and Rangpur.
</P>
<P>
In Barapukuria alone, the amount of coal reserves is estimated
at 300 million tons in a concentrated area of 5.25 square
kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The development of the Barapukuria Coal Mine Project, northwest
of Dhaka, initiated in 1994 by the Bangladesh government with
Chinese financial and technical assistance, is fast approaching
its extraction phase.  
</P>
</TEXT>
