<DOCNO> XIE19971224.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: HK External Trade Grows Steadily </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's external trade
has maintained a modest growth in a year of political transition
and regional financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
Latest government statistics show that Hong Kong's visible
trade in the first three quarters reached 2,255 billion HK dollars
(290 billion US dollars), up four percent over the same period of
1996. Re-exports rose steadily by 3.7 percent to hit 909 billion
HK dollars (116 billion US dollars), while domestic exports
dropped slightly by 1.2 percent to 155 billion HK dollars (about
20 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's external trade was not affected much by the
regional financial crisis, which toppled down many Asian
currencies to historic lows, said economists.
</P>
<P>
Andrew Fernow, head of research of Vickers Ballas Hong Kong
said that depreciation of currencies could boost export
competitiveness of other Asian economies, but Hong Kong no longer
competes head-to-head with countries like the Philippines and
Thailand on prices as it concentrates mainly on higher value added
production.
</P>
<P>
Victor Fung, chairman of the Hong Kong Trade and Development
Council (TDC), said that Hong Kong is still competitive because it
can successfully put into practice the so-called "supply chain
management" -- the science of choosing the best place for each
link in the production chain.
</P>
<P>
A Hong Kong businessman can combine the Republic of Korea's
cloth and Taiwan accessories at a factory in Indonesia, say, to
quickly produce clothes of the latest fashion for export to
Europe, Fung gave an example. There are more than 300,000 small-
and medium-sized enterprises in Hong Kong, and 40 percent of them
are involved in this kind of transnational operation.
</P>
<P>
"We don't compete on cheap prices. We are packagers and
integrators to offer a high value added "total package", ranging
from design to quality control, marketing, financing, and
customization," said Fung, who also chaired the board of Li &AMP; Fung
Group, a leading Hong Kong trading company.
</P>
<P>
The role of "packager" has boosted Hong Kong's exports of
services and offshore trade. Its exports of services have tripled
over the past decade to 288 billion HK dollars (37 billion US
dollars) in 1996, ranking ninth in the world.
</P>
<P>
Exports of services, mainly comprising transportation, travel
and trade-related services, posted robust growth between January
and June this year, up 5.3 percent to 145 billion HK dollars (18
billion US dollars). However, the TDC predicted that performance
for the whole year might be adversely affected by the slump in
tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
Offshore trade is hard to calculate, but the TDC said that this
form of trade has expanded strongly since the early 1990s to take
an increasingly share of the total external trade.
</P>
<P>
China's inland areas continue to be a powerful engine pushing
Hong Kong's trade forward steadily. In the first three quarters
this year, Hong Kong re-exported to and from the inland areas a
total of 851 billion HK dollars (109 billion US dollars) worth of
goods and services, an increase of five percent over the same
period of 1996. At the same time, Hong Kong's domestic exports to
the inland areas rose by 3.6 percent. The inland areas remain the
largest trading partner of Hong Kong.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
