<HEADLINE> HK People Have Positive Outlook of Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 24 (Xinhua) -- The year 1997 has seen the
highest confidence level of Hong Kong people in the prospects of
the city and the "One Country, Two Systems" principle, the local
press reported today.
</P>
<P>
When reviewing its regular surveys conducted in 1997, the
social sciences research center under Hong Kong University
observed that 74 percent of the residents are confident about Hong
Kong's future this year, higher than 56 percent for 1994, 58
percent for 1995 and 63 percent for 1996.
</P>
<P>
It was notable that the confidence level edged up from 72
percent in the first half of 1997 to record-high 77 percent in the
second half when the Special Administrative Region (SAR) took
shape.
</P>
<P>
People's sentiment toward the "One Country, Two System" concept
has also turned bullish. In the year 1997 record-high 61 percent
of the respondents voiced confidence in the concept, compared with
between 35 percent and 45 percent recorded for each of the
previous three years.
</P>
<P>
Sixty five percent of people are confident about "One country,
Two Systems" after the handover, up from 57 percent in the first
half of the year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a high percentage of local residents expressed their
belief in the SAR government headed by Chief Executive Tung Chee
Hwa.  
</P>
</TEXT>
