<HEADLINE> WFP Airlifts Food to Kenya's Flood-Hit Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 24 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. World Food Program
(WFP) said today it has begun Christmas airdrops of urgently
needed food to hundreds of thousands of people in Kenya,
including Somali refugees, cut off by floods in the remote
northeastern areas.
</P>
<P>
The organization will airdrop 1,500 tons of maize and high
energy biscuits to more than 200,000 people in Maudera, Garissa,
Wajir and Garsen, according to a WFP news release reaching here.
</P>
<P>
In part of these areas, people have been marooned for up to
seven weeks.
</P>
<P>
WFP is also using boats to reach people stranded along the
Tana River.
</P>
<P>
"This combination of airdrops, airlifts and boats has given
the operation a massive boost, enabling us to deliver a total of
60 tons of relief cargo each day, assisting 12,000 people on half
rations for one month," said David Fletcher, acting WFP country
director for Kenya.
</P>
<P>
" By delivering food to those living in far flung areas, we
are not only providing assistance to meet basic needs but
preventing huge population movements to the food distribution
points, which could create further health hazards and food
difficulties," he noted.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that if the rain halt immediately, it will
take up until February to reopen road services in the region
where estimatedly 300,000 people have suffered from heavy rains
caused by the El Nino weather pattern. 
</P>
</TEXT>
