<HEADLINE> World Bank Disburses $60 Million to Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 24 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has disbursed
one billion Zimbabwe Dollars (60 million U.S. dollars) in the
second structural adjustment credit facility to Zimbabwe,
Zimbabwe's Finance Minister Herbert Murerwa announced here on
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
It is a demonstration of the bank's satisfaction with the way
the government has tackled budgetary imbalances brought about by
the need to pay pensions and gratuities for former freedom
fighters, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank suspended the balance of payments support for
Zimbabwe three months ago after the government bowed to
pressure from restive former guerillas and agreed to them over an
estimated four billion Zimbabwe Dollars (235 million U.S.
dollars) in gratuities and pensions.
</P>
<P>
The money had not been budgeted for and there is fear from
the donor community, local businesses and economists that the
proposed payments to the former fighters would put the country's
national budget targets off course and trigger uncertainty in the
economy.
</P>
<P>
Other multilateral donor institutions had followed the steps of
the World Bank and withheld crucial support to Zimbabwe pending
the outcome of the government's financial plans to fund the war
veterans gratuity payments.
</P>
<P>
Murerwa said that the International Monetary Fund (IMF) had
also agreed to speed up negotiations for another enhanced
structural adjustment facility and will send a mission to
Zimbabwe next month to immediately put up a 100 million US
dollars stand-by arrangement in order to beef up Zimbabwe's
foreign reserves.
</P>
<P>
"The decision by the IMF and World Bank will trigger the
disbursement of more concessional balance of payments support
from bilateral donors and the European Union," the minister
noted.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank had also agreed to speed up the processing of a
third structural adjustment facility in support of Zimbabwe's
program for economic and social transformation, he added.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, the government has managed
to raise some 2.5 billion Zimbabwe Dollars (147 million US
dollars) to pay the ex-combatants.
</P>
<P>
Both the World Bank and the IMF were satisfied with the
government's determination to fund the war veterans packages
within the existing budget parameters, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
