<HEADLINE> Roundup: Angolan Peace Process: Hope Still Around </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Angola's peace process has
been stranded in a deadlock for several months, after a major
breakthrough in early 1997. Hope, however, is still around for
peace-thirsty Angolan people.
</P>
<P>
Following the formation of a united national army at the end
of 1996, the peace process entered into a political solution
stage in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The first progress made in this stage was the government's
recognition of UNITA (National Union for the Total Independence
of Angola) leader Jonas Savimbi as the leader of the largest
opposition party, after 15 months of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
On April 9, 66 deputies of parliament of the UNITA were sworn
into the national assembly, which was formed after Angola's first
multi-party election in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Two days later, a national unity and reconciliation
government, including four ministers and seven deputy ministers
from the UNITA was inaugurated.
</P>
<P>
The formation of this government marks a major step in
national reconciliation and the beginning of nation
reconstruction in Angola after two decades of civil war.
</P>
<P>
The peace process, however, hit snags when it came to
rebuilding government administration into UNITA-occupied areas, a
key item of the 1994 Lusaka peace accord signed by UNITA and the
Angolan government.
</P>
<P>
It seems that UNITA is reluctant to give up power in areas
under its control, especially areas of strategic importance.
</P>
<P>
In more than one cases, its members and supporters were
reportedly involved in skirmishes disrupting local government
inaugurations. They refused to recognize the leadership of local
governments and even went to the point of tearing up national
flags.
</P>
<P>
UNITA's uncooperation has actually put the peace process to a
halt. It was at this point that the United Nations (U.N.)
Security Council decided to impose sanctions on it in August,
with a view to bringing it back to the peace track.
</P>
<P>
U.N.'s sanctions include the closure of UNITA representative
offices overseas and a ban on its officials from overseas
travels.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. demands that UNITA completely disarm its personnel,
transform its radio into an independent commercial one and
cooperate in rebuilding local governments.
</P>
<P>
UNITA did take some measures under international pressure, but
these steps are definitely not enough to save the peace process.
</P>
<P>
In the latest development, the government last Thursday issued
an ultimatum to the UNITA urging it to observe all the
regulations under the Lusaka peace process by January 22 next
year.
</P>
<P>
While it is doubtful if the ultimatum could force the UNITA
back to the peace process, as it was in the case of the U.N.
sanctions, observers, however, believe that hope is still alive
for the peace process to step out of the current deadlock.
</P>
<P>
Both the government and the UNITA have repeatedly confirmed
their commitment to continuing the peace process. What is more
important, both sides have realized that they could not afford
going into another war as that war will never solve their
problem.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the two sides have agreed to hold a summit meeting
between President Dos Santos and UNITA leader Savimbi to iron out
issues facing them.
</P>
<P>
Final peace and unity in Angola is now around the corner if
only both sides show more political courage supported with
actions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
