<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chissano Hails Positive Trend in Solving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican President Joaquim
Chissano has expressed satisfaction over some progress which has
been made recently in solving African conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Speaking here Tuesday while receiving the New Year greetings
from foreign missions based in the Mozambican capital, Chissano
said the end of tension in the Great Lakes region is a positive
trend toward the elimination of conflict centers in the African
continent.
</P>
<P>
Encouraged by the positive results from the Somali peace talks
ended in Cairo on Monday, Chissano urged various Somali clans to
continue seek solutions through negotiations in a bid to make the
long-awaited peace, Noticias reported today.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the genocide incident on the borders of Rwanda
and the Democratic Republic of Congo, as well as the manslaughter
in Sierra Leone and the Comoros, the Mozambican president uttered
his condemnation, saying that "at a time when the consolidation
of democracy is becoming a global factor, and peace and order, it
is unacceptable for someone to still use arms as a means to grasp
power."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chissano also appealed for international support
for the implementation of sanctions imposed on Angola, so as to
make active contribution to "putting an end to the Angola Peace
Process." 
</P>
</TEXT>
