<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Swimming Rebounds from Atlanta Doldrums (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 24 (Xinhua) -- With the Atlanta Olympic Games
fadding farther behind and the World Championships drawing closer,
1997 looks like a quiet year for swimming.
</P>
<P>
Quiet if there had been no Chinese Eighth National Games.
</P>
<P>
Chinese women swimmers, who won only one gold in Atlanta, shook
off shadow of the lackluster show by setting two world records,
nine Asian marks and 11 world year's best times in the Games in
Shanghai last October.
</P>
<P>
The sensational performance reminded sports world that China,
whose women won 12 out of 16 golds at the Rome World Championships
in 1994 and glittered with four golds in Barcelona Olympic Games,
re-emerged as one of the powerhouses in the world.
</P>
<P>
Chen Yan from northeast China's Liaoning Province became the
most prolific star in the National Games by bagging four
individual gold medals plus two world records.
</P>
<P>
The 16-year-old excited herself and the fans in the women's 400
meters individual medley by clocking four minutes and 34.79
seconds, shattering the 15-year-old mark of 4:36.10 set by Petra
Schneider of former East Germany on August 1, 1982.
</P>
<P>
And only two days later, Chen savored her second feat by
clocking 2:11.27 to surpass another world record of 2:11.65 in the
200m individual medley, which was eventually won by Wu Yanyan of
Guangxi.
</P>
<P>
Wu, 19, became the surprise heroine in the event with 2:09.72,
beating Chen into second place and putting her own name in the
world record book.
</P>
<P>
Chen, who stands 1.78 meters and is believed a born swimmer,
also triumphed in the 200m, 400m and 800m freestyle events,
declaring the beginning of her era.
</P>
<P>
Chen's road to the top was checkered with ups and downs when
she caught the spotlight in the Olympic trials with four golds but
ended with fiasco in Atlanta after failing to make any of the
finals in three events.
</P>
<P>
The strong comeback in the National Games helped her restore
confidence and she is ready to make another storm in the world
arena.
</P>
<P>
"I sincerely hope that I can do better in the coming World
Swimming Championships in Perth next January," she said.
</P>
<P>
For Wu, who also shone in the Olympic trials but slipped into
slump in Atlanta, the world record was a juicy fruit of 12-year
hard training.
</P>
<P>
"She has swum 3,000 kilometers in the pool this year," coach Wu
Jicai said of his protege.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971224.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Swimming Rebounds from Atlanta Doldrums (2-last) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Joining hands with youngsters to drag China out of the doldrums
was Le Jingyi, the lone swimming champion for China in Atlanta and
world record holder of 50m and 100m freestyles.
</P>
<P>
Le, who was named the outstanding swimmer at the Rome World
Championships for setting those two records, won the 100m
freestyle with 54.02 in the National Games -- just nine hundredths
of a second outside her world mark.
</P>
<P>
The 22-year-old disputed rumors that she could retire after the
Games. "I have not thought of the issue. I might take part in the
Sydney Olympic Games."
</P>
<P>
But people doubted whether she can hold her post in Sydney
after she lost her 50m speciality to a 19-year-old Shan Ying and
failed to make the 200m freestyle finals.
</P>
<P>
In evaluating the performance of the women swimmers in the
Games, Chinese sports officials warned both the young and veterans
against pre-mature conceit and the tough challenge ahead in the
world.
</P>
<P>
"They can hardly peak again in just three months, and I don't
expect them to put up very good results in the world
championships," said Yuan Jiawei, general secretary of the Chinese
Swimming Association.
</P>
<P>
Yuan Weimin, vice minister of the Chinese Physical Culture and
Sports Commission, also slapped at the near-sightedness of
provincial sports officials, who urged their athletes to peak in
the national events instead of encouraging them to reserve the
best for big meetings.
</P>
<P>
"Chinese athletes should compete in top form in international
and world events instead of focusing on internal strife," he said.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere in the pool, the passing year also saw the Chinese
shine sporadically in the low-profile World Short-Course
Championships in Gothenburg and the World Cup short-course
tournaments.
</P>
<P>
In the World Short-Course Championships in April, the Chinese
foursome, composed of Wang Luna, Chen Yan, Nian Yun and Shan Ying,
broke the world 4X200m freestyle relay record by clocking 7:51.92.
</P>
<P>
While the women stole the limelight in the year from short to
long courses, their men counterparts also tried hard not to be
overlooked.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Chengji proved he was still the best man swimmer of China
by winning three individual gold medals. His time in the 50m
freestyle and 100m butterfly were ranked sixth and eighth
respectively this year in the world.
</P>
<P>
Zeng Qiliang also swam the year's third best time in the 100m
breaststroke, a great stride following his record seventh
finishing at the Atlanta Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Ming, deputy head coach of the national team, said that
through hard efforts of several generations, it was only a matter
of time for the Chinese men swimmers to bring back Olympic or
world titles.
</P>
<P>
"They are no longer satisfied with national or Asian gold
medals," Zhou said. "They are eager to win titles at world major
tournaments." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971224.0188 </DOCNO>
