<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top Ten Chinese Sports Stories of 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Following are the top ten
Chinese sports stories in the year of 1997 selected by the Sports
News Service of the Xinhua News Agency:
</P>
<P>
1. The Eighth National Games were held in Shanghai in October
with 46 delegations participating in 28 sports. A total of seven
world records in Olympic sports were shattered in the games.
</P>
<P>
2. Cyclist Wong Kam-po won the first ever national games gold
medal for Hong Kong Special Administrative Region after China
resumed its sovereignty over the territory in July.
</P>
<P>
3. The Chinese men's soccer team failed for the fifth time in
nearly 20 years to qualify for the World Cup finals. The Chinese
women's team won their sixth title in the Asian Championships in
December.
</P>
<P>
4. Chinese women's runners once again proved their strength in
the middle and long-distance events when Jiang Bo and Dong Yanmei
broke the 5,000 meters world record at the Eighth National Games.
Now the Chinese hold four world records in middle and
long-distance races.
</P>
<P>
5. The Chinese badminton team reinstated their leading position
in the world after winning 15 titles in major tournaments.
</P>
<P>
6. The Chinese men's volleyball team, coached by former ace
player Wang Jiawei, re-emerged as a continental power when it won
for the first time in 18 years the Asian championship title and
beat Olympic champion the Netherlands at the World Grand Champions
Cup in Japan in November.
</P>
<P>
7. The Chinese weightlifters kept their leading place in the
world championships. Cui Wenhua made a breakthrough for Chinese
hercules when he broke the European dominance in heavey weight
class by winning three golds in the 108kg catagory in the
championships.
</P>
<P>
8. The Chinese team won six titles at the 44th World Table
Tennis Championships in Manchester, England, in April.
</P>
<P>
9. The Chinese men's team won the crown for the third time in a
row at the World Gymnastic Championships in Lausanne,
Switzerland. The women's team finished third.
</P>
<P>
10. The Chinese women's squad failed for the first time since
1975 to play in the final at the Asian Basketball Championships.
</P>
