<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Re-Proposes VAT Refunds for Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Foreign tourists could expect
to get value-added tax (VAT) back for the goods they buy in
Thailand next year as the Thai Finance Ministry is re-proposing a
VAT refund program.
</P>
<P>
The Bangkok Post Wednesday said that the revenue department
under the ministry had agreed in principle to the refund program,
which is expected to be forwarded to the cabinet for approval
soon.
</P>
<P>
If the plan won the cabinet approval, it will be implemented
beginning on the new year, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, foreign tourists who buy goods at a designated
outlet may receive the VAT refund on the day they depart Thailand,
according to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Yet, foreign tourists have to pay the traditional one percent
fee on the value of the goods, it added.
</P>
<P>
The refund proposal emerged years ago to make Thailand an
international shopping hub to match Hong Kong and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
However, the idea has been floating for years as the Thai
government was reluctant to provide the refunds.
</P>
<P>
Thai Deputy Finance Minister Pichet Phanvichartkul recently
said that if the proposal is adopted this time, the government
will be responsible for the refunds initially and then it may
transfer the responsibility to private firms.  
</P>
</TEXT>
