<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 24 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Agency for
International Development (USAID) and the Asia Foundation have
agreed to fund the women's empowerment program in Nepal, The
Rising Nepal newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The program aims to increase women's access to and control over
productive resources and to increase their influence over
decision-making at the household and community levels, the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the USAID will grant a total of 5.5
million U.S. dollars over the next three years to implement the
Women's Microenterprise and Literacy Program in 23 districts
across the Terai plain in southern Nepal and hilly areas in the
country's mid-western development region.
</P>
<P>
Over 100,000 women will benefit from the program, the paper
said.
</P>
<P>
Likewise, the Asia Foundation, a U.S.-based international
non-governmental organization, will provide 1.9 million dollars
over the next three years for the Women's Rights, Responsibilities
and Advocacy Program, which aims to help the same group of women
to increase knowledge on legal rights and civic responsibilities,
the newspaper said.  
