<HEADLINE> Argentina To Fight Soccer Hooliganism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Argentina is setting up a
special police unit with powers to deal with the nation's
worsening soccer violence after a fan's death at a first division
match, officials said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Ulises Fernandez, a 24-year-old fan of Huracan was shot dead in
the head last Friday at a local derby against San Lorenzo when
fans pelting each other with stones outside the stadium.
</P>
<P>
Argentine Football Association chief Julio Grondona said at a
meeting of security and soccer authorities that a decree would be
passed to enanble the government's Security Department the direct
responsibility to deal with soccer violence.
</P>
<P>
A database of known hooligans would also be set up to
effectively trace the crime records of those soccer violence
criminals, said Grondona.
</P>
<P>
Security Secretary Adrian Pelacchi said the death of Fernandez
had nothing to do with the decision to rush through the
long-stalled Sports Violence Law as they were "not waiting for a
fan's death to speed up the signiture of the decree".
</P>
<P>
Under the law, Pelacchi will have powers to order the temporary
or permanernt closure of grounds with repeated problems with
violence.
</P>
<P>
Argetina has suffered a lot from soccer violence and in April
1994, a gang of Boca Juniors supporters ambushed fans from arch
rivals River Plate and killed two of them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
