<HEADLINE> Passengers Held Partly Responsible for Air Flight Delays </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 24 (Xinhua) -- As high as 5,100 air flight
delays occurred this year were caused by passengers, according to
a national meeting held here.
</P>
<P>
The punctuality of passenger planes in China in the first 11 months
of this year was only 74 percent, lower than last year, the
meeting held by Civil Aviation Administration of China (CAAC) said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting said some of the passengers missed the descending
time due to shopping and dozing off; others were unable to catch
plane on time due to being unable to present right documentation
or hiding hazardous goods in luggages.
</P>
<P>
In a serious case on December 7, a flight running between
Shanghai and Dalian was delayed two hours and 47 minutes merely
because of a joke made by an irresponsible passenger who claimed
he had a bomb in his suitcase when being ordered to move the
suitcase from the aisle. He was later detained for 15 days.
</P>
<P>
"We sincerely hope passengers show more concern and support to
our work," said a CAAC official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
