<HEADLINE> India's Corporations in Throes of Slowdown: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 24 (Xinhua) -- India's business leaders
suggested that demand should be stimulated through the
government's public expenditure on development activities,
specially infrastructure, said a survey here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted by the Federation of Indian Chamber of
Commerce and Industry covering 303 corporations in the medium,
large and small sectors, has revealed that corporations are in the
throes of major slowdown.
</P>
<P>
In fact, 50 percent of the respondents felt "if the trend is
not corrected, the economy would slip into a recessionary phase."
</P>
<P>
Forty-five percent of the respondents were of the view that the
current slowdown would continue for more than a year and 30
percent felt that the slowdown would remain in effect for another
nine to 12 months, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
The survey revealed that lack of demand and overcapacity have
been a major deterrent factor affecting the growth. The recent
political instability also had a dampening effect on investments.
 
</P>
