<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Second Accused of Oklahoma Bombing Convicted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 23 (Xinhua) -- A federal jury Tuesday
convicted Terry Nichols, one of the two men charged with the
Oklahoma city bombing, of conspiracy to use a weapon of mass
destruction and involuntary manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
The convictions mean the jurors did not believe Nichols carried
out premeditated murder but acknowledge that the eight federal
officers were killed as a result of Nichols' action.
</P>
<P>
But the seven-women and five-men jury in Denver, Colorado,
acquitted Nichols of two other counts -- using a weapon of mass
destruction and destroying the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building
in Oklahoma, the bombing of which left 168 dead and 500 injured on
April 19, 1995.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors said they accept the verdict and are ready to move
on to the penalty phase.
</P>
<P>
Nichols, 42, frowned as he listened to the jury's decision,
news reports said. He would possibly face a death sentence.
</P>
<P>
The other suspect in the bombing, Nichols' former Army buddy
Timothy McVeigh, was convicted and sentenced to death earlier this
year.
</P>
<P>
United States District Judge Richard Matsch ordered the jury
back to the U.S. Courthouse in Denver next Monday to begin the
sentencing phase of Nichols.
</P>
<P>
Matsch scheduled a Wednesday hearing on a defense motion to
overturn the verdict.
</P>
<P>
In June, another jury took 23 hours to convict McVeigh on all
11 counts and sentenced him to die after 11 hours of
deliberations. McVeigh is at the federal prison in Florence,
Colorado, and his case is on appeal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
