<HEADLINE> Thai Government Stands Firm to Cancel Hopewell Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 24 (Xinhua) -- The Chuan Leekpai government
has reaffirmed the Thai government's stand to scrap the Hopewell
elevated rail and road project contract.
</P>
<P>
The Chuan cabinet at its weekly meeting on Tuesday confirmed
that it will stick to the previous government's decision to cancel
the contract.
</P>
<P>
The Thai Transport and Communications Ministry will send an
official letter to inform Hopewell (Thailand) Co. of the
government's stand within the week.
</P>
<P>
The Chuan cabinet had agreed with the ministry to seek an order
from the civil court to scrap the project to save time and ensure
the right to use the site, as Hopewell might resort to
time-consuming arbitration to solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
The Chavalit Yongchaiyudh government made a decision in
September this year to revoke the Hopewell contract, citing the
delay in construction over the past six years.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers said that so far, only a fifth of the 60 km
multi-deck system was completed, with the cost estimated at 3.7
billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government will seek other private parties to take
over the project, the newspapers said.  
</P>
