<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Red Tape Hampers Rehabilitation in Northern Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Bureaucratic red tape of the
Sri Lankan government departments has resulted in delays in
proposed rehabilitation, reconstruction and resettlement projects
in the Jaffna peninsula, informed sources said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Rehabilitation and Reconstruction Authority for North
(RRAN), which functions under the direction of President Chandrika
Kumaratunga, and international humanitarian relief agencies in Sri
Lanka have experienced certain difficulties in implementing Jaffna
projects, the sources pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The RRAN and the United Nations Development Program (UNDP) have
made arrangements to implement 11 of the 34 proposed projects,
funded by the UNDP, from the beginning of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Despite a series of discussions officials have not approved the
projects. The sources said: "Every time we met they wanted to make
amendments to the projects."
</P>
<P>
Many officials responsible for approving and monitoring ongoing
or proposed projects in Jaffna have not visited that region in the
recent two years, said the sources, who asked not to be named.
</P>
<P>
"Here we have foreign donors willing to fund projects but
bureaucratic red tape has caused serious problems. Decisions are
made by people who have not visited Jaffna for the past two
years," they said.
</P>
<P>
They noted that people in Jaffna expect the government to
improve their living conditions as soon as possible.
Meanwhile, even though the UNDP had agreed to fund the Jaffna
mine clearing project, the green light has not been given to
launch the project.
</P>
<P>
The sources stressed that the government's military operations
against the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam in the peninsula must
be supported by intensified efforts to improve civil
administration and facilities in the region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
