<DOCNO> XIE19971224.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF, World Bank Approve Debt Reduction Package for Guyana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) and the World Bank today announced an agreement to
support a debt reduction package for Guyana under the initiative
for Heavily Indebted Poor Countries (HPIC).
</P>
<P>
The total assistance to be provided to Guyana by all of its
external creditors will reduce Guyana's external debt burden by a
quarter, about 253 million U.S. dollars in Net Present Value (NPV)
terms.
</P>
<P>
This is estimated to translate into debt-service relief over
time of close to 500 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The IMF and World Bank will provide assistance with a NPV value
of 35 million dollars and 27 million dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
In recognition of Guyana's exceptional achievements in
implementing reform it was agreed that the completion point for
the delivery of the debt reduction package will be one year from
now, to December 1998. This is two-years shorter than the normal
three-year waiting period under the HIPC initiative.
</P>
<P>
However, the delivery of the debt reduction package from the
IMF and the World Bank is subject to confirmation from Guyana's
other creditors that they will provide their share and
satisfactory implementation of reforms agreed by the Government.
</P>
<P>
The IMF will provide its assistance at the completion point in
the form of a grant into an escrow account to be used to pay
debt-services falling due to the IMF.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the World Bank will use the special HIPC Trust Fund,
to which it has already contributed 750 million dollars, to
purchase debts owed by Guyana to the International Development
Association (IDA), the World Bank's concessionary lending arm to
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
These debts will then be canceled. m The fiscal resources
released will be used by the government to strengthen and broaden
its social program, especially in basic health and education.
</P>
<P>
Guyana is the fourth country to benefit under the HIPC
debt-reduction initiative, raising the total debt relief committed
under the initiative in 1997 to about 1.2 billion dollars in NPV
terms, or about two billion dollars in debt service reduction over
time.
</P>
<P>
Guyana is also the first country to qualify under criteria
established under this initiative, in April 1997, for highly open
economies with heavy fiscal burdens of external debt despite
strong efforts in mobilizing revenue.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, the Inter-American Development Bank (IDB) also
issued a statement endorsing the decision to grant debt relief for
Guyana, the second country in South America to benefit from the
HIPC initiative.
</P>
<P>
The IDB will grant debt relief to Guyana for a total of 48.1
million dollars in present value.
</P>
<P>
Bolivia, the first Western Hemisphere country to benefit from
the initiative, was awarded 155 million dollars in debt relief, in
terms of present value by the IDB last September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971224.0217 </DOCNO>
