<HEADLINE> San Francisco Squeezes Tobacco Ads' Further </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 23 (Xinhua) -- San Francisco is likely to
ban tobacco advertising in most of the metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
Members of the Board of Supervisors passed an ordnance Monday
to ban tobacco advertising on billboards, bus shelters, sandwich
boards, banners, and signs and posters visible from the streets.
</P>
<P>
If the ordnance is approved by Mayor Willie Brown, violators
could be fined up to 100 U.S. dollars. Tobacco advertising would
only be permitted on vehicles, on billboards facing highways and
inside stores, said reports on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The measure is intended to stop tobacco companies from
"maliciously and intentionally taking advantages of our kids,"
Supervisor Gavin Newsom said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
California laws taking effect next year will ban tobacco
advertising within 1,000 feet (305 meters) of schools and
playgrounds. 
</P>
