<HEADLINE> Poland to Rescue Kidnapped Poles in Chechnya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Poland has set up a special
group and will send representatives to Chechnya as soon as
possible in order to rescue five Poles, who were kidnapped in the
Russian breakaway region on December 17.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Bronislaw Geremek said here Tuesday that the
five young men were aid volunteers, who started their Chechnya
trip on December 14 by a car, following Polish Gdanskie transport
food vehicles.
</P>
<P>
They were kidnapped by unidentified people after meeting with
former Chechen President Zelimkhan Yandarbijev on December 17.
</P>
<P>
The missing people's car was found on the way to their
destination Samaszki, a village 30 kilometers west of the region's
capital Grozny, with tires pierced by bullets.
</P>
<P>
It was believed that none of them was harmed, because there was
no bloodstain at the site.
</P>
<P>
Geremek said this is the first time that Poles were kidnapped.
So far, it has not been clear why they were kidnapped, due to
money or political aim?
</P>
<P>
There were reportedly about 200 people kidnapped in the Chechen
region, including two British. The ransom was three million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Polish Prime Minister Jerzy Buzek is worried about the case. He
said that the case involved human lives, it will be treated with
the utmost care. 
</P>
</TEXT>
