<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Telecom Targets 300,000 New Phones by 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 24 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lanka Telecom (SLT)
will invest 23 billion rupees (383 million U.S. dollars) next year
in order to provide 300,000 new telephone connections in two
years, the Daily News newspaper said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The new investment would form the basis of a three-year
restructuring plan of the SLT, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Chief Executive Officer of SLT Hideki Kamitsuma was quoted as
saying that their immediate task was to expedite new connections.
To achieve the target, the company has to provide at least 10,000
new connections each month.
</P>
<P>
The CEO said a total of 70,000 connections have been
established this year, compared with 20,000 connections in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Currently the company has 252 telephone exchanges with a
456,610 switching capacity throughout the country. In 1998 the
capacity will be expanded to 635,000.
</P>
<P>
The SLT also proposes to re-balance its tariff structure next
year by revising the local call charges upwards. At present local
calls are heavily subsidized at the expense of international call
charges. About 80 percent of the SLT's income came from
international call charges.
</P>
<P>
The SLT was partly privatized in August when the government
sold a 35 percent stake to the NTT of Japan for 225 million
dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
