<HEADLINE> Two Cubs of Manchurian Tigers Born in Yantai Zoo of China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Two cubs of the Manchurian
tiger, one of the most endangered species in the world, have been
born in the zoo of Yantai, a coastal city in east China's
Shandong Province.
</P>
<P>
The cubs, one male and one female, were born on October 24
and they have since been fed artificially. Experts say, artificial
feeding is more difficult than being fed by the dam.
</P>
<P>
Their mother, 6-year-old, delivered four cubs that day, but
only two survived. The tiger has a natural first cub surviving
rate of five percent, the experts say.
</P>
<P>
The successful births of the two cubs have made the Yantai zoo
the record holder in China in artifically breeding Manchurian
tigers.
</P>
<P>
The cubs' father is four years old.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
