<HEADLINE> No Blocks in Way of Tajik Coalition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Tajik President Emomali
Rakhmonov and the United Tajik Opposition (UTO) leader, Sayid
Abdullo Nuri, said there is no further obstacle to forming a
coalition government.
</P>
<P>
They made the remark following talks on Tuesday, the Interfax
news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to form a new government with 30 percent of the
posts given to the opposition, as stipulated by a general peace
agreement earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
On June 27, 1997, the two sides signed a landmark peace accord
in Moscow, ending the central Asian coluntry's four-year civil war.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, opposition forces were to integrate with
government troops or lay down weapons, and a joint government was
to be formed.
</P>
<P>
Tajikistan plunged into internal strife soon after gaining
independence in 1991. Islamic opposition forces, the main rivals
of the Tajik government, set up bases in mountainous border areas
between Tajikistan and Afghanistan, and launched a guerrilla war.
</P>
<P>
The peace process started in 1994 on the initiative of the
United Nations, leading to the signing of the June peace
agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
