<DOCNO> XIE19971224.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Armed Men Kill 43 Indigenous People in Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, December 23 (Xinhua) -- A group of armed men
killed at least 43 indigenous people and injured dozens of others
in a latest attack in the southeastern Mexican state of Chiapas, a
rebel army spokesman said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman Javier Elorriaga of the rebel Zapatista National
Liberation Army (EZLN) said the attack occurred on Monday in the
town of Acteal, in the municipality of Chenalho.
</P>
<P>
Elorriaga blamed the manslaughter, during a local celebration
event, on paramilitary groups and said the federal government was
"guilty of not fulfilling the peace accords reached with the EZLN."
</P>
<P>
Officials of the Health Secretariat in the city of San
Cristobal de las Casas said more than 20 injured, including women
and children, were taken to a hospital in the region.
</P>
<P>
The assault was the bloodiest in Chiapas since more than 130
people died in the EZLN uprising in January 1994.
</P>
<P>
Chiapas Attorney General Marco Antonio Bezares said an official
commission was heading to the site to investigate the case, as
ordered by President Ernesto Zedillo.
</P>
<P>
"Many people have lost their lives, we condemned the action,
and the Chiapas government is concerned," the local official said.
</P>
<P>
Here in this Mexican capital city, President Zedillo told Chief
State Prosecutor Jorge Madrazo to "spare no effort in identifying
and punishing those who carried out this crime."
</P>
<P>
Violences in Chenalho broke out six months ago when the
sympathizers of the EZLN and the followers of the ruling
Institutional Revolutionary Party began fighting for power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
