<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Labor Service Effective in Helping Poor Farmers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Labor export has become one of
the most effective way for poor farmers in Gansu Province to tide
over a meagre year.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-six year-old Yang Qing and his four-member family in
Dangchang County would have been in trouble if he had not gone to
the neighboring Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, helping collect
cotton to make some money.
</P>
<P>
His village had been plagued by droughts for four successive
years. He had a poor harvest from his farmland this year. Although
the local government provided his family with relief grain, he
still could not make the ends meet.
</P>
<P>
Like other laborers, Yang left the village to earn a living for
the whole family. By now the province has exported nearly two
million of rural laborers to other provinces, autonomous regions
and municipalities, and they have earned a total of 2.1 billion
yuan (about 250 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Wang Wulin and his wife have been left alone at home in Wudu
County since their two children went out as migrant
laborers. Their son even hasn't written back telling where he is
now. But the old couple doesn't worry about their children, as
they have remitted home regularly.
</P>
<P>
After years of working outside of their home villages, an
increasing number of migrant laborers have begun to return to the
villages to make a new career out of the skills or experience they
have gained outside.
</P>
<P>
"Years ago, we had to persuade farmers to go outside to make a
living. But now they have seen the good of it and do it
voluntarily," said a local township government official.
</P>
<P>
The province has opened labor service agencies in seven
provinces, autonomous regions and cities, providing information
for laborers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
