<DOCNO> XIE19971224.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bank of Italy Cuts Discount Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Italy today cut its
official discount rate by 0.75 percent, from 6.25 to 5.50 percent.
</P>
<P>
The central bank also cut its short-term advance rate by the
same amount, from 7.75 to 7.00 percent.
</P>
<P>
The rate cut, urged by Italian businessmen and politicians,
was widely expected following the approval of a 1998 budget
earlier today.
</P>
<P>
The budget is aimed at bringing Italy's deficit below the 3
percent ratio required to join the European single currency.
</P>
<P>
Pressure has also mounted in recent weeks as the rates on the
central bank's own repurchase operations have been consistently
below the official discount rate.
</P>
<P>
Today's rate cut was the first of its kind since June 30, when
the Bank of Italy snipped half a point off the discount rate to
take it from 6.75 to 6.25 percent.
</P>
<P>
On January 22 1997, the bank cut the rate by 0.75 to 6.75
percent.
</P>
<P>
December's 1.5 percent inflation rate was the lowest since
February 1969, except for the 1.4 percent in June and September
this year.
</P>
<P>
Italy's annual inflation rate averages at 1.7 to 1.8
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
