<HEADLINE> Holyfield-Lewis Fight Strikes Snag </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 24 (Xinhua) -- A title bout between
Evander Holyfield and Lennox Lewis to crown an unified heavyweight
champion ran into a money snag on Tuesday as guarantees demanded
by the fighters were too high.
</P>
<P>
HBO matchmaker Lou DibBella said that there was "a big gap "
over how much money it would take to make the fight in the talks
with Holyfield's promoter Don King, and his lawyer, Jim Thomas.
</P>
<P>
They had previously met Monday at a midtown hotel after Lewis's
camp in London and said the fighters had agreed in principle to
fight in April.
</P>
<P>
DiBella would not comment on specifics of the purse but said
the number would double that of Holyfield-Moorer match last month
from which Holyfield made 20 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Lewis's manager Frank Maloney said on Monday the unification
fight between Britain's World Boxing Council champion Lewis and
Holyfield would carry a purse of between 40-50 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Both fighters have long expected to meet to determine one true
heavyweight champion and it would be the first time the three
heavyweight belts have been united since Riddick Bowe held them
all in 1992 after beating Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
World Boxing Association and International Boxing Federation
champion Holyfield's record is 35-3 and Lewis 32-1. 
</P>
