<HEADLINE> Panamanian Government Urged to Explain Role of MADC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, December 23 (Xinhua) -- A Panamanian legislator
said today that the people ought to be completely informed of the
future role and nature of the projected Multilateral Anti-Drug
Center (MADC) between Panama and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Aleman Boyd, President of the Legislative Commission on Drugs,
demanded that the ruling Democratic Revolutionary Party (DRP) make
clear what kind of operations would be carried out by the MADC.
</P>
<P>
The lawmaker's remarks came as a meeting took place on the
issue in Miami between Panama's negotiator Jorge Ritter and his
U.S. counterpart Thomas McNamara.
</P>
<P>
Aleman Boyd said that the decision on whether to set up the
center must be made by the people through a referendum.
</P>
<P>
The MADC will be established at the U.S. Howard Air Base,
located at the riversides of the Panama Canal and will count on
military personnel to operate the technical equipment.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, the countries that have been interested in joining
the center are Brazil, Mexico, Colombia, the United States and
Panama.
</P>
<P>
The MADC project was sharply criticized by opposition parties
in Panama. They argued that the facility will mean an extension
of the U.S. military domain in the region, beyond the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The United States is supposed to retreat its troops from the
Panama Canal facilities by December 31, 1999 according to
Torrijos-Carter Treaties signed in 1977 by Panama and the United
States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
