<HEADLINE> Tomb of Duke Unearthed in Sichuan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Archaeologists in southwest
China's Sichuan Province have unearthed a tomb which buried a
duke of Sichuan and his wife, the first of its kind ever
discovered in the province.
</P>
<P>
The tomb is located in Jingjiang district of Chengdu, the
provincial capital city.
</P>
<P>
The couple was buried in the same tomb but placed in separate
rooms. Archaeologists have concluded that the tomb had been robbed
before, leaving only more than 190 pieces of clay sculptures and
potteries
</P>
<P>
The most prominent feature of the tomb is its well-preserved
structure, and its beautiful sculptures, experts said.
</P>
<P>
The tomb was built in the Ming Dynasty (1368-1644). 
</P>
