<DOCNO> XIE19971224.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rabbani Calls for Negotiated Settlement of Afghan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 23 (Xinhua) -- Ousted Afghan president
Burhanuddin Rabbani on Tuesday called for a peaceful settlement of
the Afghan issue "through negotiations," according to a report by
the Associated Press of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Talking to the local media at the Peshawar Airport in North
West Frontier province soon after his arrival from Afghanistan,
Rabbani said that "this is my tacit opinion that no issue could be
solved through war because it is known to every body that the only
way to the solution of Afghan problem is possible through
negotiations."
</P>
<P>
In reply to a question about his talks with the Taliban, he
said that "we think that talks with Taliban is the only way for
restoration of peace in Afghanistan."
</P>
<P>
He appreciated efforts of the Pakistani government for
restoration of peace in Afghanistan and said, "we have come here
to discuss the Afghan problem so as to achieve peace in our
country."
</P>
<P>
He also said "we hope, Pakistan and Iran, our neighboring
countries who along with Saudi Arabia helped us during Jehad (Holy
War) against the former Soviet Union, could play a vital role in
the settlement of the Afghan crises."
</P>
<P>
Rabbani said that "let us forget the past and work hand in hand
for the solution of the issue and resolve the tragedy."
</P>
<P>
Rabbani noted that he had held talks with Pakistani Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif in Tehran during the recent Eighth Summit of
the Organization of Islamic Conference (OIC) and had pleaded that
Pakistan, Iran and Saudi Arabia should come forward and initiate a
peace process in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the purpose of his current visit to Pakistan,
Rabbani said he had come here with a purpose to pave the way for a
peaceful solution of the Afghan problem.
</P>
<P>
Rabbani categorically said, "we are opposed to interference
from any foreign quarter in the internal affairs of Afghanistan,"
adding that "we think and all sides should think that there is no
way for solving the Afghan problem through war."
</P>
<P>
He further suggested that Pakistan, Iran and Saudi Arabia
should intensify efforts for peace within the framework of OIC and
under the auspices of UN.  
</P>
</TEXT>
