<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Approves Three Billion U.S. Dollar Loan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank approved
today three billion U.S. dollar loan to help South Korea's
economic reconstruction, the first of several measures to back the
country to recover from financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The loan, with a term of 10 years of repayment and aimed at
achieving long-term stabilization and a revival of growth, is a
single-tranche fast-disbursing operation.
</P>
<P>
The resources will be utilized to focus on reforms in the
financial sector and capital markets, improvements of corporate
governance and competitiveness policies.
</P>
<P>
"We regard this loan as a symbol of Korea's commitment to
structural reforms that in time will help restore the health of a
fundamentally sound economy," James D. Wolfensohn, the President
of the World Bank said today. "Our long-term view of Korea's
economic prospects remains strongly favorable. We look forward to
working closely with the Government to help move the country
forward."
</P>
<P>
The World Bank's loan is part of a record 57 billion dollar
bailout package for South Korea. But the cash disbursement needed
quickly to satisfy short-term creditors who are demanding 15
billion dollars from South Korea by the end of the year. An
additional 1 billion dollars in short-term loans is due in
January, 1998.
</P>
<P>
South korea began borrowing from the World Bank in 1962, and
was "graduated" from its borrowing program at the end of 1994. The
loan represents a resumption of the World Bank's lending to the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
