<HEADLINE> U.S. Warns Its Citizens Not to Travel to Guyana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The United States today
advised its citizens not to travel to Guyana due to the outbreak
of violence that followed the election last week of an
American-born president.
</P>
<P>
"While there is no reason to believe that violence would
specifically be targeted at Americans, the potential for unrest
remains," the State Department announced.
</P>
<P>
Janet Jagan, a 77-year-old grandmother from Chicago, was sworn
in on Friday as the first woman president of the former British
colony.
</P>
<P>
Last week, police fired tear gas on the streets of Georgetown,
the capital of the country, to disperse angry mobs of opponents
protesting against the outcome of the election.
</P>
<P>
Jagan, who left Chicago for Guyana 54 years ago, says she ran
for president reluctantly to carry on the political legacy of her
husband, who died in office nine months ago.
</P>
<P>
She will govern the ethnically-mixed and sparsely-populated
South American country of only 800,000 for five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
