<HEADLINE> U.S.: U-2 Continues to Fly over Iraq during Ramadan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. U-2 spy planes will
continue to take their surveillance flights over Iraq during the
Muslim holy month of Ramadan which begins next week, the
Pentagon said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
There would be "some overflights and presumably some (U.N.
weapons) inspection trips after Ramadan begins," spokesman
Kenneth Bacon told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Bacon said the U-2 flights have been continuing and the
latest one took place "one day or two ago", which lasted four
hours. "It did what it was supposed to do and came back. It was
unchallenged," he added.
</P>
<P>
Bacon said Iraq's forces "still appear to be organizing their
SA-2 long-range missiles in a way that would position them to
perhaps be able to shoot down a U-2 flying over central Iraq."
</P>
<P>
"But we have seen no attempts to do that and, indeed, the
threatening rhetoric that they used back in early November has
ceased," he added.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has accused the United States of using the U-2 planes to
gather information for another attack against it.
</P>
<P>
Bacon said Iraq also was moving around other missile systems
and air defense units are appearing "as if they're trying to set
up ambushes for the planes flying over southern Iraq."
</P>
<P>
But again he said "there have been no threats or attempts to
ambush any of these fighters recently" from the Iraq forces.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
