<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Mediator to Travel to Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S Middle East Mediator
Dennis Ross will visit Israel and the Palestinian Authority early
next month in preparation for their leaders' separate talks with
President Bill Clinton, the State Department said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Foley told reporters that Ross
was likely to arrive in the region on Jan. 5, although details
were still being worked out.
</P>
<P>
But he said his talks with both Israeli and Palestinian
officials will focus mainly on several interim issues which have
been pending since the last Israeli-Palestinian peace deal in
1995.
</P>
<P>
These include a seaport and a corridor to connect Gaza with the
West Bank the Palestinian Authority controls, setting up an
industrial zone in Gaza.
</P>
<P>
Ross will try to push Israeli into suspending the construction
of Jewish homes in the West Bank and in East Jerusalem which the
Palestinian Authority claims to be its capital of a future state,
Foley said. He also will try to convince Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu to make a further withdrawal from the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Palestinian peace talks have been stuck in deadlock
for nine months since the Israeli government, in defiance of peace
accords agreed by the two sides, decided to build Jewish housing
units in Arab East Jerusalem in March.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright has tried several
times, including a trip to the Middle East and recent talks in
Europe with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, to bring the two leaders back to
the negotiating table so that the peace process could be revived.
But all the efforts she has made ended in failure.
</P>
<P>
Albright's frustration in pulling the peace process back on
track thus prompted Clinton to announce last week to meet the
Israeli and Palestinian leaders in Washington next month.
</P>
<P>
Foley said Washington is still working on the basis of separate
contacts with both Middle East leaders. And the question of any
face-to-face Netanyahu-Arafat meeting was "hypothetical" at this
stage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
