<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Welcomes Outcome of Recent Meetings between Somali </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 23 (Xinhua) -- The Security Council
today issued a presidential statement, welcoming the outcome of
meetings between the Somali leaders held in Cairo, which concluded
on December 22, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Council welcomed the decisions made by the Somali leaders
to adopt a federal system with regional autonomy and their
agreement to form a transitional government of national unity and
to hold an inclusive conference of national reconciliation through
which a presidential council and a Prime Minister will be elected.
</P>
<P>
The Council's move came after it considered the situation in
Somalia, including the recent developments in the political,
military and humanitarian fields.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, the Council reaffirmed is commitment to a
comprehensive and lasting settlement of the crisis in Somalia and
stressed the responsibility for achieving genuine national
reconciliation and peace rests with the Somali people themselves.
</P>
<P>
The Council expressed its full support for the efforts of
regional and other interested states as well as those
international and regional organizations to promote a direct
political dialogue and facilitate the emergence of a broad-based
Central Government in Somalia.
</P>
<P>
The Council called upon all Somali leaders to contribute
positively to the current momentum for peace and reconciliation
created by the significant progress achieved in Cairo and to cease
immediately all acts of violence and to observe the ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
The Council urged all states to contribute generously to the
appeals of the United Nations to ensure continued relief and
rehabilitation efforts in all regions of Somalia.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council reiterated its call that all states
fulfill their obligations to implement the embargo imposed by its
resolutions on all deliveries of weapons and military equipment to
Somalia.
</P>
<P>
It called on all states to refrain from any actions which might
exacerbate the situation in Somalia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
